{"title_page": "Anthony James (artist)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Anthony James\n| image              = Anthony James in Los Angeles 2015.jpg\n| caption            = Anthony James in his Los Angeles studio\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = 1974\n| birth_place        = England\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date)  -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = British/American\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = British/American [[art]]ist\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = [[Sculpture]], [[painting]], and experiential [[Installation art|installations]].\n| notable_works      = Portals, K\u0398 (Kalos Thanatos), Birch\n}}\n\n'''Anthony James''' is a British/American [[art]]ist based in Los Angeles, known for his monumental and experiential sculptures and installations. His work gestures towards the theatricality of [[minimalism]] and [[Formalism (art)|formalism]]. There is a focus on materiality, alchemy, and a deep respect for light and space.\n\n''\"My work is my best attempt at giving the impossible, the infinite, a physical, objective existence. The materials are merely an extension of the gesture. I start with the gesture and have spent decades distilling these concepts down to the essential. So whether I\u2019m using vanguard, illustrious materials and high technology or centuries old metal techniques \u2014 my interest is in communicating the most direct way I can. There is a minimalistic simplicity to the work, yet it expresses something infinite \u2014 it\u2019s a pluralistic paradox. I\u2019ve tried to visually demonstrate the colossally vast and the infinitesimally small \u2014 the cosmos and the divinity inside oneself.\"'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aestheticamagazine.com/impact-on-the-market/|title=Aesthetica Magazine - Impact on the Market|website=Aesthetica Magazine|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> -Anthony James, [[Aesthetica|Aesthetica Magazine]]\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nAnthony James was born in [[England]] in 1974. He studied in [[London]] at [[Central Saint Martins College of Art and Design]] and graduated with a degree in fine art painting. \n\n\"''being a child in the 70\u2019s and 80\u2019s in england \u2014 there was a lot of chaos. you know how mother nature self corrects \u2013 adapts \u2013 heals? maybe I was drawn to formalism and minimalistic art because in many ways it is inverted chaos. maybe it\u2019s my way of creating order.''\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.designboom.com/art/anthony-james-light-sculptures-opera-gallery-04-04-2020/|title=anthony james on 'the colossally vast and the infinitesimally small'|date=2020-04-05|website=designboom {{!}} architecture & design magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> -Anthony James, [[Designboom]] \n\nJames has also called New York City, Munich, and Los Angeles home. Currently, he is based in Los Angeles and operates his studio in Downtown LA. \n\n==Art==\n\n''\"My job as an artist is to make my work look effortless, but of course it\u2019s not. The human eye only hits the mistakes. I will never let your eye hit on a mistake.\u201d'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.palmspringslife.com/anthony-james-artist/|title=Anthony James Sacrifices His Ferrari 355 Spider for Artwork|date=2019-07-27|website=Palm Springs Life|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n'''[https://vimeo.com/anthonyjamesstudio Portals] / [[Plato|Platonic]] Solids / [[Archimedean solid|Archimedean]] Solids, 2008-present'''\n[[File:Anthony James Portals.jpg|thumb|[http://www.anthonyjamesstudio.com Anthony James Studio - Portals]]]\nThe sculptures, made of stainless steel, glass, and LED lights, have shown internationally to great acclaim. \n\n''\"I\u2019m interested in revealing and sharing truth. My intention is to bring an impossible concept like the idea of infinity, or the cosmos, into physical objective existence. I am attempting to express science, spirituality, and philosophy in an object the purest and most honest way I know how.\"'' \n\n'''K\u0398 Kalos Thanatos, 2008''' \n[[File:Kalos Thanatos 019 R.jpg|thumb|K\u0398 Kalos Thanatos, 2008 Anthony James]]\nJames gained international recognition in 2008 for his work Kalos Thanatos (K\u0398), Greek for \u201cbeautiful death\u201d, when he burned his [[Ferrari F355|Ferrari F335]] Spyder in a birch forest, and then displayed it in a mirrored glass box with birch tree trunks. James was inspired by the ancient Greeks, who made sacrifices to [[Aphrodite]] in birch forests.<ref>Michael Slenske, 2017, \u201cSpiritual Gangster\u201d, Cultured Magazine, pp. 194-199.</ref> [[Glenn O'Brien|Glenn O\u2019Brien]] lauded James\u2019 Kalos Thanatos by describing it as daring: \u201cI miss art going out on a limb...Just a slim limb that looks like there\u2019s at least some chance of it snapping...Anthony James burned his Ferrari and put it in a box, amid, actually, a bunch of limbs. That was going for it\u2026.this work is pretty gutsy...The car was a victim, a sacrifice old-school redux.\u201d<ref>Glenn O\u2019Brien, \u201cCasual Magic: The Art of Anthony James\u201d, Morphic Fields, Munich: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2014, pp. 58-71</ref>\n\n''\"you can\u2019t really escape yourself. you\u2019re always on the same thing. the artwork may present differently, but there is always an underlying signature theme. for me, everything is life / death / birth / rebirth somehow. it\u2019s not an intention, but it all comes back to one source. burning a ferrari and stuff \u2014 it\u2019s all instinctual. now I look back at it and \u2018beautiful death\u2019 is more of a concept than a sentence. it\u2019s bizarre. you can\u2019t escape your own destiny which is what the [[iliad]] is about.\"'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.designboom.com/art/anthony-james-light-sculptures-opera-gallery-04-04-2020/|title=anthony james on 'the colossally vast and the infinitesimally small'|date=2020-04-05|website=designboom {{!}} architecture & design magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> -Anthony James, [[Designboom]]\n\n'''The Birch Series, 2005-Present'''\n\nJames originally debuted The Birch Series in New York City in 2005. It consisted of several variously sized, vertical light boxes with young birch tree trunks inside. The sculpture series references the containment and simulation of nature. The works have mirrored sides, which give the illusion of an endless birch forest. The pieces are composed of birch trees, metal, glass, and fluorescent lights or LEDs. The birch tree is associated with magical symbolism. [[Glenn O'Brien|Glenn O\u2019Brien]] wrote about birch trees that their \u201cmagic...is rooted in [the] special relationship with fly agaric mushrooms - that famed toadstool of the red cap and white spots - which is so often associated with elves and spirits...Many anthropologists consider it to be a possible agent of the transformation of human consciousness.\u201d<ref>Glenn O\u2019Brien, \u201cCasual Magic: The Art of Anthony James\u201d, Morphic Fields, Munich: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2014, pp. 58-71.</ref> Of the series, James said, \"''I think about the containment of nature. The containment of our own nature. There\u2019s something about the individuals journey that is really at the root of it. Going into the forest \u2014 not knowing what you\u2019ll find \u2014 not knowing if you\u2019ll ever return... You can see the metaphor.\"''\n\n''\"They resemble a contradiction between like a Stanley Kubrick and Gustav Klimt. It\u2019s Gustav Klimt mourning the way they\u2019re lit, it\u2019s this endless birch forest, but everything is in too much symmetry. You know, there\u2019s something menacing there. What first appears to be beautiful is actually quite menacing in a Kubrick way.\"''  <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.interviewmagazine.com/art/anthony-james|title=Into the Mirrors: Anthony James|date=2010-09-29|website=Interview Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]\n\n'''Morphic Fields, 2014'''\n[[File:Morphic Fields Anthony James.jpg|thumb|Morphic Fields, 2014 Anthony James]]\nMorphic Fields was an exhibition of bronze and limestone pieces inspired by the scientist [[Rupert Sheldrake]]\u2019s theory of morphic resonance: \u201ca process whereby self-organizing systems inherit a memory from previous similar systems.\u201d<ref>Glenn O\u2019Brien, \u201cCasual Magic: The Art of Anthony James\u201d, Morphic Fields, Munich: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2014, pp. 58-71.</ref> Sheldrake describes his theory relative to the artistic process: \u201cEvery morphic fields starts with some creative step. Newton was the first person to think of the law of gravity. And before he\u2019d thought of it, no one else had. Since then, millions of people have been able to think of it. So all morphic fields begin with individuals\u2026Very few contemporary artists have the sense of inspiration from a transcendent source beyond the human realm. But I would argue that they are also drawing from the collective human experience. As much as there is room for individual creativity, every artist is also transcending collective memory. Artists can create new morphic fields. Yet, all art exists within a morphic field beyond the individual.\u201d<ref>Katja Eichinger, \u201cAn Interview with Rupert Sheldrake\u201d, Morphic Fields, Munich: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2014, pp. 52-57.</ref> The sculptures are created from found materials and \u201cthrough [James\u2019] process of converting...waste into bronze they morph into something very beautiful and precious.\u201d<ref>Matthias Muhling, \u201cAn Interview with Anthony James\u201d, Morphic Fields, Munich: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2014, pp. 77-89.</ref>\n\n'''Shields, 2016-Present'''\n\nShields was an exhibition of curved disks made of brass, bronze, and steel \u201cscarred with [[Minimalism|minimalist]] markings.\u201d This series \u201coperates elusively, staggering between the iconic and the arbitrary, the concrete and the alchemic, the mythical and experiential.\u201d<ref> Fort Gansevoort, https://static1.squarespace.com/static/55ee2fc1e4b0c1020ff7e01a/t/591f29c103596e77e94503c7/1495214536115/FG_AnthonyJames_PressRelease_FINAL.pdf, \u201cAnthony James/Fabulism\u201d, 2017.</ref> James describes his work as, \u201cevoking pictorial depictions of the [[cosmos]], alluding to notions of mysticism, ethereality, and science fiction, all the while anchored through the use of weighty, industrial materials such as metal.\"<ref> Fort Gansevoort, https://static1.squarespace.com/static/55ee2fc1e4b0c1020ff7e01a/t/591f29c103596e77e94503c7/1495214536115/FG_AnthonyJames_PressRelease_FINAL.pdf, \u201cAnthony James/Fabulism\u201d, 2017.</ref> The shields \u201cread as relics or artifacts from some liminal moment, as such, James attempts to locate beauty in the wake of insanity.\u201d<ref>Fort Gansevoort, https://static1.squarespace.com/static/55ee2fc1e4b0c1020ff7e01a/t/591f29c103596e77e94503c7/1495214536115/FG_AnthonyJames_PressRelease_FINAL.pdf, \u201cAnthony James/Fabulism\u201d, 2017.</ref>\n\n'''Rain Paintings, 2018'''\n[[File:Rain Painting Anthony James.jpg|thumb|Rain Paintings, 2018 Anthony James]]\nA photorealistic series made of contradictory materials: Belgian linen, gesso, and [https://www.ppgdeltron.com Deltron]. \u201cPurity is an illusion. The timeless, cleansing rain evoked by James\u2019 paintings is artificial. The viewer can encounter the work through a meditative fascination with its lucid intricacy \u2013 the eternal and universal behavior of water. And the aesthetic pleasure of this is intense. But to read it as only beautiful or mystical is to miss the logic of contradiction that gives the work its conceptual strength, the spray of toxic industrial paint onto an object recognizable to any old-master artist\u2019s apprentice. Therefore, in a larger sense, this work presents an argument for combination and exchange over homogeneity and conformity. James\u2019 new mode of painting can be read as a critique of easy simulation, of virtuality, in relation to both traditional illusionism and the digital. By layering contrasting material processes to create a seeming unity, a surface of streaming water, these works insist on the real over the hyperreal and on the assembled, heterogeneous, contested nature of that reality.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://there-there.co/therethere-exhibitions|title=exhibitions|website=there-there|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n'''Neons, 2002-present'''\n\nColorful rings of neon nod to the ancient concept of the universe as set of concentric planetary orbits. The effect is both esoteric and industrial, morphic and distinctly concrete.\n\n==Exhibitions==\n\nSelected Solo Exhibitions\n\n* 2020: [[Opera Gallery]], London, England\n*2018: Rain Paintings, There-There Gallery, Los Angeles, CA\n*2017: Portals, There-There Gallery, Los Angeles, CA\n* 2017: Shields, [http://www.fortgansevoort.com Fort Gansevoort], New York, NY\n* 2016: Maloney Fine Art, Los Angeles, CA\n* 2014: Morphic Fields, [https://www.storms-galerie.de Walter Storms Galerie], Munich, Germany\n* 2012: Consciousness And Portraits Of Sacrifice, [http://www.brandnew-gallery.com/Software/ Brand New Gallery], Milan, Italy\n* 2010: \u039a\u0398, Patrick Painter Gallery, Santa Monica, CA\n* 2007: Visionaire Gallery, New York, NY\n* 2007: Milk Gallery presented by [https://www.gavlakgallery.com/gallery Gavlak], New York, NY\n*2007: [https://www.gavlakgallery.com/gallery Gavlak], West Palm Beach, FL\n* 2006: Kantor/Feuer Window, New York, NY\n* 2005: Holasek Wier Gallery, New York, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artnet.com/magazineus/features/finch/finch3-6-06.asp|title=artnet Magazine - The Return of Anthony James|website=www.artnet.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n* 1999: Four, Four, Four Apex Art, New York, NY\n\nSelected Group Exhibitions\n\n* 2019: [https://crystalbridges.org/exhibitions/crystals/ Crystals In Art: Ancient to Today], [[Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art]], Bentonville, AR\n*2018: [https://www.art-aspen.com Art Aspen], Aspen, Colorado with [https://melissamorganfineart.com Melissa Morgan Fine Art]\n* 2014: [https://www.louise-alexander.com/exhibition/art-international-istanbul-2016/ Art International Istanbul], Istanbul, Turkey with [https://www.louise-alexander.com Louise Alexander Gallery]\n* 2011: [[The Armory Show (art fair)|The Armory Show]], New York, NY\n* 2011: The shortest distance between 2 points is often intolerable, [http://www.brandnew-gallery.com/Software/ Brand New Gallery], Milan, Italy\n* 2011: \u201cPieces of Heaven\u201d Auction, [[The Art of Elysium]], Los Angeles, CA\n* 2010: [[Art Basel]] 41, Basel, Switzerland\n* 2010: [[The Armory Show (art fair)|The Armory Show]], New York, NY\n* 2010: Angel Art Auction Presented by [[Creative Artists Agency|CAA]], Los Angeles, CA\n* 2009: Blue, Blue, Kim Light / LightBox, Los Angeles, CA\n* 2008: Getting Out Our Dreams, Otero Plassart, Los Angeles, CA\n* 2007: Some Kind of Portrait, [http://www.marcselwynfineart.com Mark Selwyn], Los Angeles, CA\n* 2007: [[The Armory Show (art fair)|The Armory Show]], New York, CA\n* 2007: [[Art Basel]], Miami, FL\n* 2006: The Monty Hall Problem, curated by [[Slater Bradley]], [[Blum & Poe|Blum and Poe]], Los Angeles, CA\n* 2006: Flaming June VI, curated by Sarah Gavlak, [http://www.spaniermanmodern.com Spanierman Modern], New York, NY\n* 2006: Color Theory and Practice, Briggs Robinson Gallery, New York, NY\n* 2006: Twenty-Five Bold Moves, curated by [https://simonwatsonarts.com Simon Watson] and Craig Hensala Of Scenic, House of Campari, New York, NY\n* 2002: Superimposition, curated by [http://www.d-hunt.com/origin.html David Hunt], [https://www.carengoldenfineart.com Caren Golden Fine Art], New York, NY\n* 2000: [[New Museum|The New Museum]], curated by [http://stefanobasilico.com/cv.html Stefano Basilico], New York, NY\n* 1999: Room With A View, Sixth @ Prince Gallery, New York, NY\n*1999: Road Show, DFN Gallery, New York, NY\n* 1999: Machine Gun Etiquette, [https://spencerbrownstonegallery.com/main Spencer Brownstone Gallery], New York, NY\n* 1999: Foul Play, Thread Waxing Space, New York, NY\n\n==Publications==\n[[File:Morphic Fields Book AnthonyJames.jpg|thumb|Morphic Fields by: Anthony James]]\n''[https://www.hatjecantz.de/anthony-james-6131-1.html?article_id=6131&clang=1 Morphic Fields Book], 2014''\n\n''Morphic Fields'' is the title of a series of twenty-one amorphous bronze sculptures with limestone bases\u2014 works created from cardboard boxes dipped in and shaped with wax and subsequently cast in bronze. This first monograph on Anthony James includes a number of offbeat essays on the artist\u2019s work. Fashion and art critic [[Glenn O'Brien|Glenn O\u2019Brien]] provided sharp-witted in\u00adsights, and writer [[Christian Kracht]] added his typically sardonic commentary. An interview with controversial biologist [[Rupert Sheldrake]] was a highly fitting contribu\u00adtion; his theory of morphic fields inspired the artist\u2019s work and the title of this publication. Other text contributions include a piece by: Matthias M\u00fchling. The book was printed in Germany and published by [https://www.hatjecantz.de Hatje Cantz Verlag].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.anthonyjamesstudio.com Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:James, Anthony}}\n[[Category:British sculptors]]\n[[Category:British male sculptors]]\n[[Category:21st-century sculptors]]\n[[Category:Postmodern artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Central Saint Martins]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Anthony James\n| image              = Anthony James in Los Angeles 2015.jpg\n| caption            = Anthony James in his Los Angeles studio\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = 1974\n| birth_place        = England\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date)  -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = British/American\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = British/American [[art]]ist\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = [[Sculpture]], [[painting]], and experiential [[Installation art|installations]].\n| notable_works      = Portals, K\u0398 (Kalos Thanatos), Birch\n}}\n\n'''Anthony James''' is a British/American [[art]]ist based in Los Angeles, known for his monumental and experiential sculptures and installations. His work gestures towards the theatricality of [[minimalism]] and [[Formalism (art)|formalism]]. There is a focus on materiality, alchemy, and a deep respect for light and space.\n\n''\"My work is my best attempt at giving the impossible, the infinite, a physical, objective existence. The materials are merely an extension of the gesture. I start with the gesture and have spent decades distilling these concepts down to the essential. So whether I\u2019m using vanguard, illustrious materials and high technology or centuries old metal techniques \u2014 my interest is in communicating the most direct way I can. There is a minimalistic simplicity to the work, yet it expresses something infinite \u2014 it\u2019s a pluralistic paradox. I\u2019ve tried to visually demonstrate the colossally vast and the infinitesimally small \u2014 the cosmos and the divinity inside oneself.\"'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aestheticamagazine.com/impact-on-the-market/|title=Aesthetica Magazine - Impact on the Market|website=Aesthetica Magazine|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> -Anthony James, [[Aesthetica|Aesthetica Magazine]]\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nAnthony James was born in [[England]] in 1974. He studied in [[London]] at [[Central Saint Martins College of Art and Design]] and graduated with a degree in fine art painting. \n\n\"''being a child in the 70\u2019s and 80\u2019s in england \u2014 there was a lot of chaos. you know how mother nature self corrects \u2013 adapts \u2013 heals? maybe I was drawn to formalism and minimalistic art because in many ways it is inverted chaos. maybe it\u2019s my way of creating order.''\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.designboom.com/art/anthony-james-light-sculptures-opera-gallery-04-04-2020/|title=anthony james on 'the colossally vast and the infinitesimally small'|date=2020-04-05|website=designboom {{!}} architecture & design magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> -Anthony James, [[Designboom]] \n\nJames has also called New York City, Munich, and Los Angeles home. Currently, he is based in Los Angeles and operates his studio in Downtown LA. \n\n==Art==\n\n'''Portals / [[Plato|Platonic]] Solids / [[Archimedean solid|Archimedean]] Solids, 2008-present'''\n[[File:Anthony James Portals.jpg|thumb|[http://www.anthonyjamesstudio.com Anthony James Studio - Portals]]]\nThe sculptures, made of stainless steel, glass, and LED lights, have shown internationally to great acclaim. \n\n''\"I\u2019m interested in revealing and sharing truth. My intention is to bring an impossible concept like the idea of infinity, or the cosmos, into physical objective existence. I am attempting to express science, spirituality, and philosophy in an object the purest and most honest way I know how.\"'' \n\n'''K\u0398 Kalos Thanatos, 2008''' \n[[File:Kalos Thanatos 019 R.jpg|thumb|K\u0398 Kalos Thanatos, 2008 Anthony James]]\nJames gained international recognition in 2008 for his work Kalos Thanatos (K\u0398), Greek for \u201cbeautiful death\u201d, when he burned his [[Ferrari F355|Ferrari F335]] Spyder in a birch forest, and then displayed it in a mirrored glass box with birch tree trunks. James was inspired by the ancient Greeks, who made sacrifices to [[Aphrodite]] in birch forests.<ref>Michael Slenske, 2017, \u201cSpiritual Gangster\u201d, Cultured Magazine, pp. 194-199.</ref> [[Glenn O'Brien|Glenn O\u2019Brien]] lauded James\u2019 Kalos Thanatos by describing it as daring: \u201cI miss art going out on a limb...Just a slim limb that looks like there\u2019s at least some chance of it snapping...Anthony James burned his Ferrari and put it in a box, amid, actually, a bunch of limbs. That was going for it\u2026.this work is pretty gutsy...The car was a victim, a sacrifice old-school redux.\u201d<ref>Glenn O\u2019Brien, \u201cCasual Magic: The Art of Anthony James\u201d, Morphic Fields, Munich: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2014, pp. 58-71</ref>\n\n''\"you can\u2019t really escape yourself. you\u2019re always on the same thing. the artwork may present differently, but there is always an underlying signature theme. for me, everything is life / death / birth / rebirth somehow. it\u2019s not an intention, but it all comes back to one source. burning a ferrari and stuff \u2014 it\u2019s all instinctual. now I look back at it and \u2018beautiful death\u2019 is more of a concept than a sentence. it\u2019s bizarre. you can\u2019t escape your own destiny which is what the [[iliad]] is about.\"'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.designboom.com/art/anthony-james-light-sculptures-opera-gallery-04-04-2020/|title=anthony james on 'the colossally vast and the infinitesimally small'|date=2020-04-05|website=designboom {{!}} architecture & design magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> -Anthony James, [[Designboom]]\n\n'''The Birch Series, 2005-Present'''\n\nJames originally debuted The Birch Series in New York City in 2005. It consisted of several variously sized, vertical light boxes with young birch tree trunks inside. The sculpture series references the containment and simulation of nature. The works have mirrored sides, which give the illusion of an endless birch forest. The pieces are composed of birch trees, metal, glass, and fluorescent lights or LEDs. The birch tree is associated with magical symbolism. [[Glenn O'Brien|Glenn O\u2019Brien]] wrote about birch trees that their \u201cmagic...is rooted in [the] special relationship with fly agaric mushrooms - that famed toadstool of the red cap and white spots - which is so often associated with elves and spirits...Many anthropologists consider it to be a possible agent of the transformation of human consciousness.\u201d<ref>Glenn O\u2019Brien, \u201cCasual Magic: The Art of Anthony James\u201d, Morphic Fields, Munich: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2014, pp. 58-71.</ref> Of the series, James said, \"''I think about the containment of nature. The containment of our own nature. There\u2019s something about the individuals journey that is really at the root of it. Going into the forest \u2014 not knowing what you\u2019ll find \u2014 not knowing if you\u2019ll ever return... You can see the metaphor.\"''\n\n'''Morphic Fields, 2014'''\n\nMorphic Fields was an exhibition of bronze and limestone pieces inspired by the scientist [[Rupert Sheldrake]]\u2019s theory of morphic resonance: \u201ca process whereby self-organizing systems inherit a memory from previous similar systems.\u201d<ref>Glenn O\u2019Brien, \u201cCasual Magic: The Art of Anthony James\u201d, Morphic Fields, Munich: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2014, pp. 58-71.</ref> Sheldrake describes his theory relative to the artistic process: \u201cEvery morphic fields starts with some creative step. Newton was the first person to think of the law of gravity. And before he\u2019d thought of it, no one else had. Since then, millions of people have been able to think of it. So all morphic fields begin with individuals\u2026Very few contemporary artists have the sense of inspiration from a transcendent source beyond the human realm. But I would argue that they are also drawing from the collective human experience. As much as there is room for individual creativity, every artist is also transcending collective memory. Artists can create new morphic fields. Yet, all art exists within a morphic field beyond the individual.\u201d<ref>Katja Eichinger, \u201cAn Interview with Rupert Sheldrake\u201d, Morphic Fields, Munich: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2014, pp. 52-57.</ref> The sculptures are created from found materials and \u201cthrough [James\u2019] process of converting...waste into bronze they morph into something very beautiful and precious.\u201d<ref>Matthias Muhling, \u201cAn Interview with Anthony James\u201d, Morphic Fields, Munich: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2014, pp. 77-89.</ref>\n\n'''Shields, 2016-Present'''\n\nShields was an exhibition of curved disks made of brass, bronze, and steel \u201cscarred with [[Minimalism|minimalist]] markings.\u201d This series \u201coperates elusively, staggering between the iconic and the arbitrary, the concrete and the alchemic, the mythical and experiential.\u201d<ref> Fort Gansevoort, https://static1.squarespace.com/static/55ee2fc1e4b0c1020ff7e01a/t/591f29c103596e77e94503c7/1495214536115/FG_AnthonyJames_PressRelease_FINAL.pdf, \u201cAnthony James/Fabulism\u201d, 2017.</ref> James describes his work as, \u201cevoking pictorial depictions of the [[cosmos]], alluding to notions of mysticism, ethereality, and science fiction, all the while anchored through the use of weighty, industrial materials such as metal.\"<ref> Fort Gansevoort, https://static1.squarespace.com/static/55ee2fc1e4b0c1020ff7e01a/t/591f29c103596e77e94503c7/1495214536115/FG_AnthonyJames_PressRelease_FINAL.pdf, \u201cAnthony James/Fabulism\u201d, 2017.</ref> The shields \u201cread as relics or artifacts from some liminal moment, as such, James attempts to locate beauty in the wake of insanity.\u201d<ref>Fort Gansevoort, https://static1.squarespace.com/static/55ee2fc1e4b0c1020ff7e01a/t/591f29c103596e77e94503c7/1495214536115/FG_AnthonyJames_PressRelease_FINAL.pdf, \u201cAnthony James/Fabulism\u201d, 2017.</ref>\n\n'''Rain Paintings, 2018'''\n\nA photorealistic series made of contradictory materials: Belgian linen, gesso, and [https://www.ppgdeltron.com Deltron]. \u201cPurity is an illusion. The timeless, cleansing rain evoked by James\u2019 paintings is artificial. The viewer can encounter the work through a meditative fascination with its lucid intricacy \u2013 the eternal and universal behavior of water. And the aesthetic pleasure of this is intense. But to read it as only beautiful or mystical is to miss the logic of contradiction that gives the work its conceptual strength, the spray of toxic industrial paint onto an object recognizable to any old-master artist\u2019s apprentice. Therefore, in a larger sense, this work presents an argument for combination and exchange over homogeneity and conformity. James\u2019 new mode of painting can be read as a critique of easy simulation, of virtuality, in relation to both traditional illusionism and the digital. By layering contrasting material processes to create a seeming unity, a surface of streaming water, these works insist on the real over the hyperreal and on the assembled, heterogeneous, contested nature of that reality.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://there-there.co/therethere-exhibitions|title=exhibitions|website=there-there|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n'''Neons, 2002-present'''\n\nColorful rings of neon nod to the ancient concept of the universe as set of concentric planetary orbits. The effect is both esoteric and industrial, morphic and distinctly concrete.\n\n==Exhibitions==\n\nSelected Solo Exhibitions\n\n* 2020: [[Opera Gallery]], London, England\n*2018: Rain Paintings, There-There Gallery, Los Angeles, CA\n*2017: Portals, There-There Gallery, Los Angeles, CA\n* 2017: Shields, [http://www.fortgansevoort.com Fort Gansevoort], New York, NY\n* 2016: Maloney Fine Art, Los Angeles, CA\n* 2014: Morphic Fields, [https://www.storms-galerie.de Walter Storms Galerie], Munich, Germany\n* 2012: Consciousness And Portraits Of Sacrifice, [http://www.brandnew-gallery.com/Software/ Brand New Gallery], Milan, Italy\n* 2010: \u039a\u0398, Patrick Painter Gallery, Santa Monica, CA\n* 2007: Visionaire Gallery, New York, NY\n* 2007: Milk Gallery presented by [https://www.gavlakgallery.com/gallery Gavlak], New York, NY\n*2007: [https://www.gavlakgallery.com/gallery Gavlak], West Palm Beach, FL\n* 2006: Kantor/Feuer Window, New York, NY\n* 2005: Holasek Wier Gallery, New York, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artnet.com/magazineus/features/finch/finch3-6-06.asp|title=artnet Magazine - The Return of Anthony James|website=www.artnet.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n* 1999: Four, Four, Four Apex Art, New York, NY\n\nSelected Group Exhibitions\n\n* 2019: [https://crystalbridges.org/exhibitions/crystals/ Crystals In Art: Ancient to Today], [[Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art]], Bentonville, AR\n*2018: [https://www.art-aspen.com Art Aspen], Aspen, Colorado with [https://melissamorganfineart.com Melissa Morgan Fine Art]\n* 2014: [https://www.louise-alexander.com/exhibition/art-international-istanbul-2016/ Art International Istanbul], Istanbul, Turkey with [https://www.louise-alexander.com Louise Alexander Gallery]\n* 2011: [[The Armory Show (art fair)|The Armory Show]], New York, NY\n* 2011: The shortest distance between 2 points is often intolerable, [http://www.brandnew-gallery.com/Software/ Brand New Gallery], Milan, Italy\n* 2011: \u201cPieces of Heaven\u201d Auction, [[The Art of Elysium]], Los Angeles, CA\n* 2010: [[Art Basel]] 41, Basel, Switzerland\n* 2010: [[The Armory Show (art fair)|The Armory Show]], New York, NY\n* 2010: Angel Art Auction Presented by [[Creative Artists Agency|CAA]], Los Angeles, CA\n* 2009: Blue, Blue, Kim Light / LightBox, Los Angeles, CA\n* 2008: Getting Out Our Dreams, Otero Plassart, Los Angeles, CA\n* 2007: Some Kind of Portrait, [http://www.marcselwynfineart.com Mark Selwyn], Los Angeles, CA\n* 2007: [[The Armory Show (art fair)|The Armory Show]], New York, CA\n* 2007: [[Art Basel]], Miami, FL\n* 2006: The Monty Hall Problem, curated by [[Slater Bradley]], [[Blum & Poe|Blum and Poe]], Los Angeles, CA\n* 2006: Flaming June VI, curated by Sarah Gavlak, [http://www.spaniermanmodern.com Spanierman Modern], New York, NY\n* 2006: Color Theory and Practice, Briggs Robinson Gallery, New York, NY\n* 2006: Twenty-Five Bold Moves, curated by [https://simonwatsonarts.com Simon Watson] and Craig Hensala Of Scenic, House of Campari, New York, NY\n* 2002: Superimposition, curated by [http://www.d-hunt.com/origin.html David Hunt], [https://www.carengoldenfineart.com Caren Golden Fine Art], New York, NY\n* 2000: [[New Museum|The New Museum]], curated by [http://stefanobasilico.com/cv.html Stefano Basilico], New York, NY\n* 1999: Room With A View, Sixth @ Prince Gallery, New York, NY\n*1999: Road Show, DFN Gallery, New York, NY\n* 1999: Machine Gun Etiquette, [https://spencerbrownstonegallery.com/main Spencer Brownstone Gallery], New York, NY\n* 1999: Foul Play, Thread Waxing Space, New York, NY\n\n==Publications==\n[[File:Morphic Fields Book AnthonyJames.jpg|thumb|Morphic Fields by: Anthony James]]\n''[https://www.hatjecantz.de/anthony-james-6131-1.html?article_id=6131&clang=1 Morphic Fields Book], 2014''\n\n''Morphic Fields'' is the title of a series of twenty-one amorphous bronze sculptures with limestone bases\u2014 works created from cardboard boxes dipped in and shaped with wax and subsequently cast in bronze. This first monograph on Anthony James includes a number of offbeat essays on the artist\u2019s work. Fashion and art critic [[Glenn O'Brien|Glenn O\u2019Brien]] provided sharp-witted in\u00adsights, and writer [[Christian Kracht]] added his typically sardonic commentary. An interview with controversial biologist [[Rupert Sheldrake]] was a highly fitting contribu\u00adtion; his theory of morphic fields inspired the artist\u2019s work and the title of this publication. Other text contributions include a piece by: Matthias M\u00fchling. The book was printed in Germany and published by [https://www.hatjecantz.de Hatje Cantz Verlag].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.anthonyjamesstudio.com Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:James, Anthony}}\n[[Category:British sculptors]]\n[[Category:British male sculptors]]\n[[Category:21st-century sculptors]]\n[[Category:Postmodern artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Central Saint Martins]]\n", "name_user": "InfinityDivinity", "label": "safe", "comment": "updated links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anthony_James_(artist)"}
{"title_page": "CTA-102", "text_new": "{{Quasar\n| name = CTA 102\n| image = \n| caption=\n| epoch = J2000\n| ra = {{RA|22|32|36.4}}<ref name=\"ned\">{{cite web | url=http://nedwww.ipac.caltech.edu/cgi-bin/nph-objsearch?objname=CTA+102 | title=CTA 102 in the NASA Extragalactic Database | accessdate=2008-12-24}}</ref>\n| dec = {{DEC|+11|43|50.9}}<ref name=\"ned\" />\n| constellation name = [[Pegasus (constellation)|Pegasus]]\n| z = 1.037<ref name=\"ned\" />\n| dist_ly = 8 billion light years (light travel distance)<ref>{{cite web | url=https://phys.org/news/2017-12-galaxy-billion-years-insight-supermassive.html | title=Galaxy 8 billion light years away offers insight into supermassive black holes | date=19 December 2017 | accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref> <br /> 11.1 billion light years (co-moving distance)\n| type = Blazar\n| appmag_v = 17.33\n| size_v =\n| notes = \n| names = CTA-102 , Q2230+11 , QSR B2230+114 , QSO J2232+1143 , 4C +11.69 , PGC 2819036 \n}}\nIn [[astronomy]], '''CTA 102''', also known by its [[B1950]] coordinates as '''2230+114''' (QSR B2230+114) and its [[J2000]] coordinates as '''J2232+1143''' (QSO J2232+1143), is a [[blazar]]-type [[quasar]] discovered in the early 1960s by a radio survey carried out by the [[California Institute of Technology]].<ref name=\"internet_encyc_space\" /> It has been observed by a large range of instruments since its discovery, including [[WMAP]], [[EGRET]], [[GALEX]], [[VLBI Space Observatory Programme|VSOP]] and [[Parkes Observatory|Parkes]],<ref name=\"ned\" /> and has been regularly imaged by the [[Very Long Baseline Array]] since 1995.<ref name=\"vlba\">{{cite web | url=http://www.physics.purdue.edu/MOJAVE/sourcepages/2230+114.shtml | title=MOJAVE Sample: 2230+114 | accessdate=2008-12-25}}</ref> It has also been detected in [[gamma rays]], and a gamma-ray flare has been detected from it.<ref name=\"atel\">{{cite web | url=http://www.astronomerstelegram.org/?read=3320 | title=Fermi LAT detection of a GeV flare from blazar CTA 102 | publisher=Astronomers Telegram | date=3 May 2011 | accessdate=3 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1963 [[Nikolai Kardashev]] proposed that the then-unidentified radio source could be evidence of a Type II or III extraterrestrial civilization on the [[Kardashev scale]].<ref name=\"internet_encyc_space\" /> Follow-up observations were announced in 1965 by Gennady Sholomitskii, who found that the object's radio emission was varying;<ref name=\"gennady\">{{cite journal | title=Variability of the Radio Source CTA-102 | last=Sholomitsky | first= G. B. | year=1965 | journal=Information Bulletin on Variable Stars | volume=83 | pages=1 | bibcode=1965IBVS...83....1S}}</ref> a public announcement of these results on April 12, 1965, caused a worldwide sensation.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=wZJMF1LD7PcC&dat=19650413&printsec=frontpage&hl=en \"Is Man Not Alone in the Universe? Space Signals Stir Experts\"], ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', April 13, 1965, p1-3</ref> The idea that the emission was caused by a civilization was rejected when the radio source was later identified as one of the many varieties of a [[quasar]].<ref name=\"internet_encyc_space\">{{cite web | url=http://www.daviddarling.info/encyclopedia/C/CTA102.html | title=CTA-102 | publisher=Internet Encyclopedia of Space; David Darling | accessdate=2008-12-14}}</ref>\n\nCTA 102 is one of the two great false alarms in the history of the [[SETI|search for extra-terrestrial life]], the other being the discovery of [[pulsars]], specifically [[PSR B1919+21]], which are rotating neutron stars.\n\nThe American [[folk rock]] band [[The Byrds]] whimsically reflected the original view that CTA-102 was a sign of extraterrestrial intelligence in their song \"C.T.A.-102\" from their 1967 album ''[[Younger Than Yesterday]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rogan|first=Johnny|authorlink=Johnny Rogan|pages=317\u2013320|year=2011|title=Byrds: Requiem for the Timeless|publisher=Rogan House|isbn=978-0-95295-408-8}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2016 CTA 102, usually glowing around [[Magnitude (astronomy)|magnitude]] +17, had a bright outburst in visible light to magnitude +11 (~250 times brighter than usual).<ref>http://www.skyandtelescope.com/observing/quasar-cta-102-historically-bright-violently-variable/</ref><ref>http://www.astronomerstelegram.org/?read=9924</ref> This likely was the most luminous [[blazar]] state ever observed,<ref>http://www.astronomerstelegram.org/?read=9868</ref> with an [[bolometric magnitude|absolute magnitude]] in excess of -32.\n\nA new outburst began in December 2017, with increased gamma-ray<ref>http://www.astronomerstelegram.org/?read=11045</ref> and optical activity.<ref>http://www.astronomerstelegram.org/?read=11081</ref> As of 22 December 2017, it has reached magnitude +14.<ref>https://www.aavso.org/apps/webobs/results/?start=2017-12-01&end=2017-12-23&num_results=25&obs_types=all&star=CTA+102</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}'We Are Not Alone' by William Sullivan 1964-1966 pg 17\n\n==See also==\n* [[LGM-1]], the first pulsar discovered, mistaken for an alien radio signal\n* [[Radio signal from HD 164595]]\n{{Extraterrestrial life}}\n\n[[Category:Search for extraterrestrial intelligence]]\n[[Category:Quasars]]\n[[Category:PGC objects]]\n[[Category:Pegasus (constellation)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Quasar\n| name = CTA 102\n| image = \n| caption=\n| epoch = J2000\n| ra = {{RA|22|32|36.4}}<ref name=\"ned\">{{cite web | url=http://nedwww.ipac.caltech.edu/cgi-bin/nph-objsearch?objname=CTA+102 | title=CTA 102 in the NASA Extragalactic Database | accessdate=2008-12-24}}</ref>\n| dec = {{DEC|+11|43|51s}}<ref name=\"ned\" />\n| constellation name = [[Pegasus (constellation)|Pegasus]]\n| z = 1.037<ref name=\"ned\" />\n| dist_ly = 8 billion light years<ref>{{cite web | url=https://phys.org/news/2017-12-galaxy-billion-years-insight-supermassive.html | title=Galaxy 8 billion light years away offers insight into supermassive black holes | date=19 December 2017 | accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref>\n| type =\n| appmag_v =\n| size_v =\n| notes = \n| names = CTA-102 , Q2230+11 , QSR B2230+114 , QSO J2232+1143 , 4C +11.69 , \n}}\nIn [[astronomy]], '''CTA 102''', also known by its [[B1950]] coordinates as '''2230+114''' (QSR B2230+114) and its [[J2000]] coordinates as '''J2232+1143''' (QSO J2232+1143), is a [[blazar]]-type [[quasar]] discovered in the early 1960s by a radio survey carried out by the [[California Institute of Technology]].<ref name=\"internet_encyc_space\" /> It has been observed by a large range of instruments since its discovery, including [[WMAP]], [[EGRET]], [[GALEX]], [[VLBI Space Observatory Programme|VSOP]] and [[Parkes Observatory|Parkes]],<ref name=\"ned\" /> and has been regularly imaged by the [[Very Long Baseline Array]] since 1995.<ref name=\"vlba\">{{cite web | url=http://www.physics.purdue.edu/MOJAVE/sourcepages/2230+114.shtml | title=MOJAVE Sample: 2230+114 | accessdate=2008-12-25}}</ref> It has also been detected in [[gamma rays]], and a gamma-ray flare has been detected from it.<ref name=\"atel\">{{cite web | url=http://www.astronomerstelegram.org/?read=3320 | title=Fermi LAT detection of a GeV flare from blazar CTA 102 | publisher=Astronomers Telegram | date=3 May 2011 | accessdate=3 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1963 [[Nikolai Kardashev]] proposed that the then-unidentified radio source could be evidence of a Type II or III extraterrestrial civilization on the [[Kardashev scale]].<ref name=\"internet_encyc_space\" /> Follow-up observations were announced in 1965 by Gennady Sholomitskii, who found that the object's radio emission was varying;<ref name=\"gennady\">{{cite journal | title=Variability of the Radio Source CTA-102 | last=Sholomitsky | first= G. B. | year=1965 | journal=Information Bulletin on Variable Stars | volume=83 | pages=1 | bibcode=1965IBVS...83....1S}}</ref> a public announcement of these results on April 12, 1965, caused a worldwide sensation.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=wZJMF1LD7PcC&dat=19650413&printsec=frontpage&hl=en \"Is Man Not Alone in the Universe? Space Signals Stir Experts\"], ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', April 13, 1965, p1-3</ref> The idea that the emission was caused by a civilization was rejected when the radio source was later identified as one of the many varieties of a [[quasar]].<ref name=\"internet_encyc_space\">{{cite web | url=http://www.daviddarling.info/encyclopedia/C/CTA102.html | title=CTA-102 | publisher=Internet Encyclopedia of Space; David Darling | accessdate=2008-12-14}}</ref>\n\nCTA 102 is one of the two great false alarms in the history of the [[SETI|search for extra-terrestrial life]], the other being the discovery of [[pulsars]], specifically [[PSR B1919+21]], which are rotating neutron stars.\n\nThe American [[folk rock]] band [[The Byrds]] whimsically reflected the original view that CTA-102 was a sign of extraterrestrial intelligence in their song \"C.T.A.-102\" from their 1967 album ''[[Younger Than Yesterday]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rogan|first=Johnny|authorlink=Johnny Rogan|pages=317\u2013320|year=2011|title=Byrds: Requiem for the Timeless|publisher=Rogan House|isbn=978-0-95295-408-8}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2016 CTA 102, usually glowing around [[Magnitude (astronomy)|magnitude]] +17, had a bright outburst in visible light to magnitude +11 (~250 times brighter than usual).<ref>http://www.skyandtelescope.com/observing/quasar-cta-102-historically-bright-violently-variable/</ref><ref>http://www.astronomerstelegram.org/?read=9924</ref> This likely was the most luminous [[blazar]] state ever observed,<ref>http://www.astronomerstelegram.org/?read=9868</ref> with an [[bolometric magnitude|absolute magnitude]] in excess of -32.\n\nA new outburst began in December 2017, with increased gamma-ray<ref>http://www.astronomerstelegram.org/?read=11045</ref> and optical activity.<ref>http://www.astronomerstelegram.org/?read=11081</ref> As of 22 December 2017, it has reached magnitude +14.<ref>https://www.aavso.org/apps/webobs/results/?start=2017-12-01&end=2017-12-23&num_results=25&obs_types=all&star=CTA+102</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}'We Are Not Alone' by William Sullivan 1964-1966 pg 17\n\n==See also==\n* [[LGM-1]], the first pulsar discovered, mistaken for an alien radio signal\n* [[Radio signal from HD 164595]]\n{{Extraterrestrial life}}\n\n[[Category:Search for extraterrestrial intelligence]]\n[[Category:Quasars]]\n[[Category:Pegasus (constellation)]]\n", "name_user": "75.134.138.206", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CTA-102"}
{"title_page": "Bo Derek", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use American English|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Bo Derek\n| image = Bo Derek by Gage Skidmore 4.jpg\n| caption = Derek in 2018\n| birth_name = Mary Cathleen Collins\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1956|11|20}}\n| birth_place = [[Long Beach, California]], U.S.\n| other_names = Kathleen Collins<br />Beau C. Shane<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.familytreenow.com/record/L6UqZvj9Ih59Y36sStWeNQ|title=John Derek, Beau C Shane \u2013 Clark County Marriage Records|author=|date=|work=familytreenow.com|accessdate=July 19, 2016}}</ref>\n| occupation = Actress\n| years_active = 1973\u2013present\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[John Derek]]|1976|1998|end=d.}}\n| partner = [[John Corbett]] (2002\u2013present)\n| children = \n| notable_works = {{ubl|''[[10 (film)|10]]'' (1979)|''[[Tarzan, the Ape Man (1981 film)|Tarzan, the Ape Man]]'' (1981)|''[[Bolero (1984 film)|Bolero]]'' (1984)|''[[Tommy Boy]]'' (1995)}}\n}}\n\n'''Bo Derek''' (born '''Mary Cathleen Collins'''; November 20, 1956)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/artist/bo-derek-p18693|title=Bo Derek|work=[[AllMovie]]|accessdate=February 1, 2018}}</ref> is an [[Americans|American]] [[film]] and [[television]] actress, [[film producer]], and model perhaps best known for her breakthrough film role in the sex comedy ''[[10 (film)|10]]'' (1979). She was directed by husband [[John Derek]] in ''[[Fantasies (film)|Fantasies]]'', ''[[Tarzan, the Ape Man (1981 film)|Tarzan, the Ape Man]]'' (both 1981), ''[[Bolero (1984 film)|Bolero]]'' (1984) and ''[[Ghosts Can't Do It]]'' (1989), all of which received negative reviews. A widow since 1998, she lives with actor [[John Corbett]]. Now in semi-retirement, she makes occasional film, television, and documentary appearances.\n\n== Early life ==\n\nDerek was born Mary Cathleen Collins in [[Long Beach, California]]. Her father, Paul Collins, was a [[Hobie Cat]] executive, and her mother, Norma (n\u00e9e White), was a make-up artist and hairdresser to [[Ann-Margret]]. Collins' parents divorced, and her mother married American [[stunt performer]] [[Bobby Bass]].\n\nCollins attended [[Narbonne High School]] and George S. Patton Continuation School, both in [[Harbor City, California]]. She remarked in a 1985 interview on ''Late Night with David Letterman'':\n\n{{quote|quote=I was 16 when I quit high school. I didn't really mean to quit. I spent about a month going to the beach surfing and sunbathing while I was supposed to be in school: when I got caught, my mom was furious. I started to go back to school, and I was really enjoying it, and then I went to go do this film with John in Greece...<ref name=\"auto\">{{YouTube|PrD50F44QqQ}}</ref>}}\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Acting ===\n\nWhile attending Narbonne High School in Los Angeles at age 16 in 1973,<ref name=\"auto\"/> Collins became sexually involved with [[John Derek]], a married man 30 years her senior. Not long after the two started dating, Derek divorced his wife, actress [[Linda Evans]]. The couple moved to Germany, where John Derek would not be subject to prosecution under California [[statutory rape]] laws because Collins was under the [[Ages of consent in the United States|age of consent]].\n\nIn 1973 John Derek began production on a film entitled ''[[Fantasies (film)|Fantasies]]'', a low-budget, English-language romantic drama starring Collins and several unknown German actors. The film was shot over a 10-day period in Greece. In an effort to capitalize on Collins' beauty, Derek worked into the film several risqu\u00e9 scenes, including brief nudity. John Derek twice re-edited the film in an effort to sell it to major studios. The film remained unreleased until 1981, at which time it received negative notices.<ref>{{cite web|title=Young Bo Derek In 'Fantasies'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/11/07/movies/young-bo-derek-in-fantasies.html?mcubz=2|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=1981-11-07|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref>\n\nCollins and John Derek married on June 10, 1976; she was 19 and he 49. By that time Derek had given his young wife a so-called [[Hollywood]] makeover: she had bleached her hair blonde and adopted the name Bo Derek.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bo Derek Then & Now|url=http://stantondaily.com/bo-derek-then-now/?singlepage=1|publisher=Stanton Daily Media Partners|date=2016|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref> In 1977 director [[Michael Anderson (director)|Michael Anderson]] cast Derek in a small role in his horror film ''[[Orca (film)|Orca - The Killer Whale]]'' (1977), in which Derek has her leg bitten off by the title character.<ref>{{cite web|title=Orca - The Killer Whale|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/orca_the_killer_whale/|publisher=Fandango|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 1979 Derek was allegedly selected over [[Melanie Griffith]], [[Heather Thomas]], and several others for the role of Jenny Hanley in the romantic comedy film ''[[10 (film)|10]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=10 (1979) - Trivia|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0078721/trivia?ref_=tt_trv_trv|publisher=IMDb.com Inc.|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref> Directed by [[Blake Edwards]], the film starred [[Dudley Moore]] as a middle-aged man who finds Derek's character to be the ideal woman. Derek's appearance in a dream sequence, racing towards Moore in a flimsy flesh-colored swimsuit, launched her status as a mainstream sex symbol. This sequence and Derek\u2019s cornrow hairstyle in the film have often been parodied. ''10'' was a critical and financial success.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 1979 Movies at the Domestic Box Office|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/box-office-records/domestic/all-movies/cumulative/released-in-1979|publisher=Nash Information Services LLC|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref>\n\nAfter ''10,'' Derek was cast in ''[[A Change of Seasons (film)|A Change of Seasons]]'' (1980), a dramatic-comedy film that featured [[Shirley MacLaine]] and [[Anthony Hopkins]]. Derek played a college student who has an affair with her older, married professor. ''A Change of Seasons'' was only a moderate box-office success, with critics reviewing it and Derek's performance unfavorably (\"The only appealing performance is Miss MacLaine's\").<ref>{{cite web|title='Change of Seasons,' Bo Derek vs. Miss MacLaine|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C03EED71638F93AA25751C1A966948260&mcubz=2|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=1980-12-19|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 1980 Derek photographed Bo twice for ''[[Playboy]]'' magazine; she was featured again in the magazine in 1981, 1984, and 1994.<ref>{{cite web|title=The 50 Hottest Celebrities Who've Posed For Playboy|url=http://uk.complex.com/pop-culture/2013/02/the-50-hottest-celebrities-whove-posed-for-playboy/|publisher=Complex Media Inc.|date=2013-02-23|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref>\n\nDerek appeared in [[MGM|MGM's]] [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system|R-rated]] ''[[Tarzan, the Ape Man (1981 film)|Tarzan, the Ape Man]]'' (1981), her first leading role in a mainstream Hollywood film. Directed by her husband, the film dealt little with [[Tarzan]] and instead focused on Derek's character of [[Jane Porter (Tarzan)|Jane Parker]], and specifically on Derek's physical attributes. Several scenes of Derek wearing revealing outfits were featured, along with nude scenes of Derek being bathed and body-painted. Prior to the film's release MGM and the film's distributor, [[United Artists]], were sued by the [[Edgar Rice Burroughs]] estate over the name of the film, as Derek's role and body overshadowed the story of Tarzan.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bo Derek Takes To The Jungle To Bring 'Tarzan' Back Alive|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/07/19/movies/bo-derek-takes-to-the-jungle-to-bring-tarzan-back-alive.html?pagewanted=all&mcubz=2|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=1981-07-19|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref> Although the film received negative reviews from many critics, ''Tarzan, the Ape Man'' became a box-office success, making over $35 million in ticket sales and becoming the [[1981 in film|15th highest-grossing film of 1981]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?yr=1981&p=.htm|title=1981 Yearly Box Office Results \u2013 Box Office Mojo|author=|date=|work=boxofficemojo.com|accessdate=July 19, 2016}}</ref> For her performance, Derek shared the [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actress]] with [[Faye Dunaway]], the latter for her starring role as [[Joan Crawford]] in ''[[Mommie Dearest (film)|Mommie Dearest]]''.\n\nDerek starred in ''[[Bolero (1984 film)|Bolero]]'' (1984). Again directed by John Derek, the film explored the female protagonist's sexual awakening, and her journey around the world to find an ideal first lover to take her virginity. Its sexual nature, along with its substantial use of nudity, resulted in the film receiving an [[X rating]], usually reserved for [[pornographic]] or extremely violent horror films. Critical reviews for ''Bolero'', including Derek's performance, were negative (\"[Bo Derek] would be a lot more appealing if she tried less assiduously to please\"),<ref>{{cite web|title=Film: Bo Derek in 'Bolero'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/09/01/movies/film-bo-derek-in-bolero.html?mcubz=2|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=1984-09-01|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref> and the film failed to recoup its production costs.<ref>{{cite web|title=1984 Yearly Box Office Results|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?yr=1984|publisher=IMDb.com Inc.|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref> For her performance in ''Bolero'' Derek won her second [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actress]]. The film received other [[Golden Raspberry Awards]]: Worst Picture, Worst Director (John Derek), Worst Screenplay (John Derek), Worst New Star ([[Olivia d'Abo]]), and Worst Musical Score ([[Peter Bernstein (composer)|Peter Bernstein]] and [[Elmer Bernstein]]).\n\nAfter a five-year hiatus Derek returned to feature films with the drama/comedy/fantasy ''[[Ghosts Can't Do It]]'' (1989). The final collaboration of Derek with her husband as director, ''Ghosts Can't Do It'' was a failure both critically (a \"cinematic abomination\")<ref>{{cite web|title=Ghosts Can't Do It|url=http://www.allmovie.com/movie/ghosts-cant-do-it-v19688|publisher=Allmovie|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref> and financially.<ref>{{cite web|title=Your Movie Sucks|url=http://www.ultimatemovierankings.com/your-movie-sucks/|publisher=ultimatemovierankings.com|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref> For her performance in ''Ghosts Can't Do It'', during which she delivered such lines as \"You have my heart...how can I live without my heart,\" Derek won her third [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actress]]. The film also won [[Golden Raspberry Awards]] for Worst Picture, Worst Director (John Derek), and Worst Supporting Actor ([[Donald Trump]]).\n[[File:Bo Derek 1998.jpg|thumb|Derek in 1998]]\nFollowing ''Ghosts Can\u2019t Do It'' Derek returned to acting in the television movies ''Hot Chocolate'' (1992) and ''Shattered Image'' (1994), and the straight-to-video film ''[[Woman of Desire]]'' (1994). In 1995 Derek appeared in the comedy film ''[[Tommy Boy]]''. For that performance Derek was nominated for a [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress]] but ultimately lost to [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] for the latter's performance in ''[[Four Rooms]]''.\n\nIn 1998 Derek guest-starred on four episodes of ''[[Wind on Water]].'' In 1999 she appeared on ''[[The Drew Carey Show]]'', and in the early 2000s she had guest roles on the shows ''[[Family Law (TV series)|Family Law]]'', ''[[Queen of Swords (TV series)|Queen of Swords]]'', ''[[Two Guys, a Girl and a Pizza Place]],'' ''[[Lucky (TV series)|Lucky]]'', ''[[Still Standing (TV series)|Still Standing]]'', and ''[[7th Heaven (TV series)|7th Heaven]]''.\n\nAt the [[20th Golden Raspberry Awards]] in 2000, Derek was nominated for Worst Actress of the Century, sharing the nomination with Madonna (the eventual winner), [[Brooke Shields]], [[Elizabeth Berkley]], and [[Pia Zadora]].\n\nDerek appeared in several more feature films during the 2000s, including ''[[Frozen with Fear]]'' (2000), ''[[The Master of Disguise]]'' (2002), for which she received her second [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress]] nomination, and ''[[Malibu's Most Wanted]]'' (2003). In 2006 Derek starred in 40 episodes of the 65-episode [[telenovela]] series ''[[Fashion House]]''. Derek had a featured role in the 2015 made-for-TV campy horror film ''[[Sharknado 3: Oh Hell No!]]''. Derek was reported to have participated in the 2016 [[Comedy Central]] [[roast (comedy)|roast]] of [[Rob Lowe]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2016/08/17/peyton-manning-bo-derek-comedy-central-roast-rob-lowe|title=Peyton Manning, Bo Derek, Rob Riggle set to roast Rob Lowe|publisher=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=19 August 2016}}</ref> but is absent from the eventual cast list.<ref>{{cite web|title=Comedy Central Roast of Rob Lowe|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6038506/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=2017-02-19}}</ref>\n\n=== Political ===\n\nDerek, who describes herself as [[Independent politician|independent]] with generally more [[libertarian]] views, supported [[George H.&nbsp;W. Bush]] in 1988 and 1992, and campaigned for his son [[George&nbsp;W. Bush]] in 2000 and 2004, and she appeared at both Republican conventions. In a January 2011 interview with ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'', she said she had voted for [[Barack Obama]] in 2008. She has appeared at events with bachelor Republican Congressman [[David Dreier]] of Southern California.<ref>[http://larryflynt.com/notebook.php?id=88 \"Congressman David Dreier: Gay & Ashamed\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051221182800/http://larryflynt.com/notebook.php?id=88 |date=December 21, 2005 }}, Larry Flynt.com</ref>\n\nWhen [[White House Chief of Staff]] [[Josh Bolten]] was asked about his relationship with Derek on the edition of April 30, 2006, of ''[[Fox News Sunday]]'' with [[Chris Wallace]], Bolten said she was a friend and a \"strong supporter of the President\".{{Citation needed|date=July 2013}} In 2006, she was appointed to the board of trustees of the [[John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts]] by President George W. Bush, on the operations committee.<ref>[http://www.kennedy-center.org/states/state.cfm?state=CA \"The Kennedy Center Activity Report for California\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080522084811/http://www.kennedy-center.org/states/state.cfm?state=CA |date=May 22, 2008 }} Kennedy Center web site</ref>\n\nIn 2012 Derek endorsed [[Mitt Romney]] for president.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/06/14/the-gop-s-two-faced-celeb-bashing-of-obama-s-parker-wintour-fundraiser.html|title=The GOP's Two-Faced Celeb Bashing of Obama's Parker-Wintour Fundraiser|first=Michelle|last=Cottle|date=June 14, 2012|work=[[The Daily Beast]] |accessdate=July 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\n=== Horse owner and activist ===\n\nA horse lover and riding enthusiast since childhood, Derek owns [[Andalusian horse]]s and is a spokesperson for the [[Animal Welfare Institute]]'s campaign to end horse slaughter through passage of federal and state legislation. On February 5, 2002, she published her autobiography entitled ''Riding Lessons: Everything That Matters in Life I Learned from Horses'' ({{ISBN|0-06-039437-4}}). She serves on the [[California Horse Racing Board]].\n\n=== Wounded veterans advocate ===\n\nDerek is a national honorary chairperson for [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs|Veterans Affairs]]' National Rehabilitation Special Events. She attended the 17th annual Disabled Veterans Winter Sports Clinic in [[Snowmass Village, Colorado]]. In 2003 she received the VA's highest honor from [[United States Secretary of Veterans Affairs|Secretary of Veterans Affairs]], [[Anthony Principi]]. Derek makes appearances on [[United Service Organizations]] tours. The [[Special Forces Association]] named her an honorary [[Special Forces (United States Army)|Green Beret]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www1.va.gov/opa/pressrel/pressrelease.cfm?id=698 |title = Bo Derek named honorary Green Beret |accessdate = January 18, 2008 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070813211713/http://www1.va.gov/opa/pressrel/pressrelease.cfm?id=698 |archive-date = August 13, 2007 |url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nDerek's father, Paul Collins, was a radio operator during the Korean war. Both her stepfather and late husband, John Derek, were veterans.\n\n=== Relationships ===\n\n[[File:Chandran Rutnam with John and Bo Derek.jpeg|thumb|right|Bo Derek with husband John Derek and [[Chandran Rutnam]]]]\n\nJohn and Bo moved to Germany and returned to the United States soon after Bo's 18th birthday; they married in 1976 and remained so until his death from heart failure in 1998.<ref>{{cite news |title = Obituary:John Derek |url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/obituary-john-derek-1157309.html |accessdate = January 15, 2012 |newspaper = The Independent |first = Tom |last = Vallance |date = May 25, 1998 }}</ref>\n\nSince 2002, she has been involved with actor [[John Corbett]].<ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1082778/Im-happy-says-Bo-Derek-opens-time-romance-Sex-And-The-Citys-John-Corbett.html 'I'm so happy', says Bo Derek as she opens up for the first time about romance with ''Sex and the City''{{'s}} John Corbett]</ref> She continues to live in California with her sister, brother-in-law, and their two children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebiographychannel.co.uk/biographies/bo-derek.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-02-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222162445/http://www.thebiographychannel.co.uk/biographies/bo-derek.html |archivedate=February 22, 2014 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n\n{{Anchor|Awards|Accolades}}\n* 1980 (Nominated): [[Golden Globe Award for New Star of the Year \u2013 Actress|Golden Globe Award for New Star of the Year in a Motion Picture \u2013 Female]] in ''10''\n* 1982 (Won): [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actress]] in ''Tarzan, the Ape Man''\n* 1985 (Won): Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actress in ''Bolero''\n* 1991 (Won): Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actress in ''Ghosts Can't Do It''\n* 1996 (Nominated): [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress]] in ''Tommy Boy''\n* 2000 (Nominated): Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actress of the Century in ''Tarzan, the Ape Man'', ''Bolero'', ''Ghosts Can't Do It'', etc.\n* 2002 (Nominated): Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress in ''The Master of Disguise''\n\n== Acting credits ==\n\n=== Film ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n| '''Film'''\n| '''Year'''\n| '''Role'''\n| '''Notes'''\n|-\n| ''[[Orca (film)|Orca]]''\n| 1977\n| Annie\n| AKA: ''Orca: The Killer Whale'' (for some releases).\n|-\n| ''[[10 (film)|10]]''\n| 1979\n| Jenny Hanley\n| Nominated \u2013 [[Golden Globe Award for New Star of the Year \u2013 Actress|Golden Globe Award for New Star of the Year in a Motion Picture \u2013 Female]]\n|-\n| ''[[A Change of Seasons (film)|A Change of Seasons]]''\n| 1980\n| Lindsey Rutledge\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Fantasies (film)|Fantasies]]''\n| 1981\n| Anastasia\n| Billed as: Kathleen Collins. Filmed in 1973; legally her \"film debut\".\n|-\n| ''[[Tarzan, the Ape Man (1981 film)|Tarzan, the Ape Man]]''\n| 1981\n| Jane Parker\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actress]]\n|-\n| ''[[Bolero (1984 film)|Bolero]]''\n| 1984\n| Ayre \"Mac\" MacGillivery\n|-\n| ''[[Ghosts Can't Do It]]''\n| 1990\n| Katie O'Dare Scott\n|-\n| ''[[Woman of Desire]]''\n| 1993\n| Christina Ford\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Tommy Boy]]''\n| 1995\n| Beverly Barish-Burns Callahan\n| Nominated \u2013 [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress]]\n|-\n| ''Sunstorm''\n| 2001\n| Victoria Warren\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Frozen with Fear]]''\n| 2001\n| Katherine Sullivan\n|\n|-\n| ''Horror 101''\n| 2001\n| Miss Allison James\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Master of Disguise]]''\n| 2002\n| Herself\n| [[Cameo appearance]]<br /> Nominated \u2013 [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress]]\n|-\n| ''[[Malibu's Most Wanted]]''\n| 2003\n| Bess Gluckman\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Boom (film)|Boom]]''\n| 2003\n| Herself\n| Cameo appearance\n|-\n| ''[[5 Weddings]]''\n| 2017\n| Mandy Singh Dhaliwal\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n| '''Program'''\n| '''Year'''\n| '''Role'''\n| '''Notes'''\n|-\n| ''Hot Chocolate''\n| 1992\n| BJ Cassidy\n| [[Television movie]]\n|-\n| ''Shattered Image''\n| 1994\n| Helen Allgood\n| Television movie\n|-\n| ''[[Wind on Water]]''\n| 1998\n| Ciel Connolly\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[The Drew Carey Show]]''\n| 1999\n| Herself\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[Family Law (TV series)|Family Law]]''\n| 2000\n| Camille Weller\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[Queen of Swords (TV series)|Queen of Swords]]''\n| 2000\n| Mary Rose\n| 1 episode [[The Witness (Queen of Swords)|\"The Witness\"]]\n|-\n| ''[[Murder at the Cannes Film Festival]]''\n| 2000\n| Thada Pryce\n| Television movie\n|-\n| ''[[Two Guys, a Girl and a Pizza Place]]''\n| 2001\n| Susan Bergen\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Lucky (TV series)|Lucky]]''\n| 2003\n| Joan\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[Still Standing (TV series)|Still Standing]]''\n| 2005\n| Mrs. Rose Grundy\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[7th Heaven (TV series)|7th Heaven]]''\n| 2003\u201305\n| Mrs. Kinkirk\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| ''Crusader''\n| 2005\n| Nicola Markham\n| Television movie\n|-\n| ''[[Fashion House]]''\n| 2006\n| Maria Gianni\n| 40 episodes\n|-\n| ''The Hunt for the I-5 Killer''\n| 2011\n| Seaver\n| Television movie\n|-\n| ''[[Chuck (TV series)|Chuck]]''\n| 2012\n| Herself\n| Season 5, Episode 10 \"Chuck Versus Bo\"\n|-\n| ''[[CSI: Miami]]''\n| 2012\n| Joanna Toring\n| Season 10, Episode 14\n|-\n| ''[[Sharknado 3: Oh Hell No!]]''\n| 2015\n| May Wexler\n| Television movie\n|-\n| ''[[The Last Sharknado: It's About Time]]''\n| 2018\n| May Wexler\n| Television movie\n|}\n\n== Production credits ==\n\n=== Film ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n| '''Film'''\n| '''Genre'''\n| '''Year'''\n| '''Role'''\n| '''Notes'''\n|-\n| ''[[Love You (film)|Love You]]''\n| Porn\n| 1979\n| Producer\n| John Derek directed the film.{{cn|date=November 2018}}\n|-\n| ''[[Ghosts Can't Do It]]''\n| Romantic Comedy\n| 1989\n| Producer, Actor\n| \n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.angelfire.com/rock2/rockinterviews/boderek.html Interview with Bo Derek]\n* {{IMDb name|0000137}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Derek, Bo}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Long Beach, California]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:California Republicans]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American libertarians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use American English|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Bo Derek\n| image = Bo Derek by Gage Skidmore 4.jpg\n| caption = Derek in 2018\n| birth_name = Mary Cathleen Collins\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1956|11|20}}\n| birth_place = [[Long Beach, California]], U.S.\n| other_names = Kathleen Collins<br />Beau C. Shane<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.familytreenow.com/record/L6UqZvj9Ih59Y36sStWeNQ|title=John Derek, Beau C Shane \u2013 Clark County Marriage Records|author=|date=|work=familytreenow.com|accessdate=July 19, 2016}}</ref>\n| occupation = Actress\n| years_active = 1973\u2013present\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[John Derek]]|1976|1998|end=d.}}\n| partner = [[John Corbett]] (2002\u2013present)\n| children = \n| notable_works = {{ubl|''[[10 (film)|10]]'' (1979)|''[[Tarzan, the Ape Man (1981 film)|Tarzan, the Ape Man]]'' (1981)|''[[Bolero (1984 film)|Bolero]]'' (1984)|''[[Tommy Boy]]'' (1995)}}\n}}\n\n'''Bo Derek''' (born '''Mary Cathleen Collins'''; November 20, 1956)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/artist/bo-derek-p18693|title=Bo Derek|work=[[AllMovie]]|accessdate=February 1, 2018}}</ref> is an [[Americans|American]] [[film]] and [[television]] actress, [[film producer]], and model perhaps best known for her breakthrough film role in the sex comedy ''[[10 (film)|10]]'' (1979). She was directed by husband [[John Derek]] in ''[[Fantasies (film)|Fantasies]]'', ''[[Tarzan, the Ape Man (1981 film)|Tarzan, the Ape Man]]'' (both 1981), ''[[Bolero (1984 film)|Bolero]]'' (1984) and ''[[Ghosts Can't Do It]]'' (1989), all of which received negative reviews. A widow since 1998, she lives with actor [[John Corbett]]. Now in semi-retirement, she makes occasional film, television, and documentary appearances.\n\n== Early life ==\n\nDerek was born Mary Cathleen Collins in [[Long Beach, California]]. Her father, Paul Collins, was a [[Hobie Cat]] executive, and her mother, Norma (n\u00e9e White), was a make-up artist and hairdresser to [[Ann-Margret]]. Collins' parents divorced, and her mother married American [[stunt performer]] [[Bobby Bass]].\n\nCollins attended [[Narbonne High School]] and George S. Patton Continuation School, both in [[Harbor City, California]]. She remarked in a 1985 interview on ''Late Night with David Letterman'':\n\n{{quote|quote=I was 16 when I quit high school. I didn't really mean to quit. I spent about a month going to the beach surfing and sunbathing while I was supposed to be in school: when I got caught, my mom was furious. I started to go back to school, and I was really enjoying it, and then I went to go do this film with John in Greece...<ref name=\"auto\">{{YouTube|PrD50F44QqQ}}</ref>}}\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Acting ===\n\nWhile attending Narbonne High School in Los Angeles at age 16 in 1973,<ref name=\"auto\"/> Collins became sexually involved with [[John Derek]], a married man 30 years her senior. Not long after the two started dating, Derek divorced his wife, actress [[Linda Evans]]. The couple moved to Germany, where John Derek would not be subject to prosecution under California [[statutory rape]] laws because Collins was under the [[Ages of consent in the United States|age of consent]].\n\nIn 1973 John Derek began production on a film entitled ''[[Fantasies (film)|Fantasies]]'', a low-budget, English-language romantic drama starring Collins and several unknown German actors. The film was shot over a 10-day period in Greece. In an effort to capitalize on Collins' beauty, Derek worked into the film several risqu\u00e9 scenes, including brief nudity. John Derek twice re-edited the film in an effort to sell it to major studios. The film remained unreleased until 1981, at which time it received negative notices.<ref>{{cite web|title=Young Bo Derek In 'Fantasies'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/11/07/movies/young-bo-derek-in-fantasies.html?mcubz=2|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=1981-11-07|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref>\n\nCollins and John Derek married on June 10, 1976; she was 19 and he 49. By that time Derek had given his young wife a so-called [[Hollywood]] makeover: she had bleached her hair blonde and adopted the name Bo Derek.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bo Derek Then & Now|url=http://stantondaily.com/bo-derek-then-now/?singlepage=1|publisher=Stanton Daily Media Partners|date=2016|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref> In 1977 director [[Michael Anderson (director)|Michael Anderson]] cast Derek in a small role in his horror film ''[[Orca (film)|Orca - The Killer Whale]]'' (1977), in which Derek has her leg bitten off by the title character.<ref>{{cite web|title=Orca - The Killer Whale|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/orca_the_killer_whale/|publisher=Fandango|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 1979 Derek was allegedly selected over [[Melanie Griffith]], [[Heather Thomas]], and several others for the role of Jenny Hanley in the romantic comedy film ''[[10 (film)|10]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=10 (1979) - Trivia|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0078721/trivia?ref_=tt_trv_trv|publisher=IMDb.com Inc.|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref> Directed by [[Blake Edwards]], the film starred [[Dudley Moore]] as a middle-aged man who finds Derek's character to be the ideal woman. Derek's appearance in a dream sequence, racing towards Moore in a flimsy flesh-colored swimsuit, launched her status as a mainstream sex symbol. This sequence and Derek\u2019s cornrow hairstyle in the film have often been parodied. ''10'' was a critical and financial success.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 1979 Movies at the Domestic Box Office|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/box-office-records/domestic/all-movies/cumulative/released-in-1979|publisher=Nash Information Services LLC|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref>\n\nAfter ''10,'' Derek was cast in ''[[A Change of Seasons (film)|A Change of Seasons]]'' (1980), a dramatic-comedy film that featured [[Shirley MacLaine]] and [[Anthony Hopkins]]. Derek played a college student who has an affair with her older, married professor. ''A Change of Seasons'' was only a moderate box-office success, with critics reviewing it and Derek's performance unfavorably (\"The only appealing performance is Miss MacLaine's\").<ref>{{cite web|title='Change of Seasons,' Bo Derek vs. Miss MacLaine|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C03EED71638F93AA25751C1A966948260&mcubz=2|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=1980-12-19|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 1980 Derek photographed Bo twice for ''[[Playboy]]'' magazine; she was featured again in the magazine in 1981, 1984, and 1994.<ref>{{cite web|title=The 50 Hottest Celebrities Who've Posed For Playboy|url=http://uk.complex.com/pop-culture/2013/02/the-50-hottest-celebrities-whove-posed-for-playboy/|publisher=Complex Media Inc.|date=2013-02-23|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref>\n\nDerek appeared in [[MGM|MGM's]] [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system|R-rated]] ''[[Tarzan, the Ape Man (1981 film)|Tarzan, the Ape Man]]'' (1981), her first leading role in a mainstream Hollywood film. Directed by her husband, the film dealt little with [[Tarzan]] and instead focused on Derek's character of [[Jane Porter (Tarzan)|Jane Parker]], and specifically on Derek's physical attributes. Several scenes of Derek wearing revealing outfits were featured, along with nude scenes of Derek being bathed and body-painted. Prior to the film's release MGM and the film's distributor, [[United Artists]], were sued by the [[Edgar Rice Burroughs]] estate over the name of the film, as Derek's role and body overshadowed the story of Tarzan.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bo Derek Takes To The Jungle To Bring 'Tarzan' Back Alive|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/07/19/movies/bo-derek-takes-to-the-jungle-to-bring-tarzan-back-alive.html?pagewanted=all&mcubz=2|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=1981-07-19|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref> Although the film received negative reviews from many critics, ''Tarzan, the Ape Man'' became a box-office success, making over $35 million in ticket sales and becoming the [[1981 in film|15th highest-grossing film of 1981]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?yr=1981&p=.htm|title=1981 Yearly Box Office Results \u2013 Box Office Mojo|author=|date=|work=boxofficemojo.com|accessdate=July 19, 2016}}</ref> For her performance, Derek shared the [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actress]] with [[Faye Dunaway]], the latter for her starring role as [[Joan Crawford]] in ''[[Mommie Dearest (film)|Mommie Dearest]]''.\n\nDerek starred in ''[[Bolero (1984 film)|Bolero]]'' (1984). Again directed by John Derek, the film explored the female protagonist's sexual awakening, and her journey around the world to find an ideal first lover to take her virginity. Its sexual nature, along with its substantial use of nudity, resulted in the film receiving an [[X rating]], usually reserved for [[pornographic]] or extremely violent horror films. Critical reviews for ''Bolero'', including Derek's performance, were negative (\"[Bo Derek] would be a lot more appealing if she tried less assiduously to please\"),<ref>{{cite web|title=Film: Bo Derek in 'Bolero'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/09/01/movies/film-bo-derek-in-bolero.html?mcubz=2|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=1984-09-01|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref> and the film failed to recoup its production costs.<ref>{{cite web|title=1984 Yearly Box Office Results|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?yr=1984|publisher=IMDb.com Inc.|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref> For her performance in ''Bolero'' Derek won her second [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actress]]. The film received other [[Golden Raspberry Awards]]: Worst Picture, Worst Director (John Derek), Worst Screenplay (John Derek), Worst New Star ([[Olivia d'Abo]]), and Worst Musical Score ([[Peter Bernstein (composer)|Peter Bernstein]] and [[Elmer Bernstein]]).\n\nAfter a five-year hiatus Derek returned to feature films with the drama/comedy/fantasy ''[[Ghosts Can't Do It]]'' (1989). The final collaboration of Derek with her husband as director, ''Ghosts Can't Do It'' was a failure both critically (a \"cinematic abomination\")<ref>{{cite web|title=Ghosts Can't Do It|url=http://www.allmovie.com/movie/ghosts-cant-do-it-v19688|publisher=Allmovie|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref> and financially.<ref>{{cite web|title=Your Movie Sucks|url=http://www.ultimatemovierankings.com/your-movie-sucks/|publisher=ultimatemovierankings.com|accessdate=2017-06-13}}</ref> For her performance in ''Ghosts Can't Do It'', during which she delivered such lines as \"You have my heart...how can I live without my heart,\" Derek won her third [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actress]]. The film also won [[Golden Raspberry Awards]] for Worst Picture, Worst Director (John Derek), and Worst Supporting Actor ([[Donald Trump]]).\n[[File:Bo Derek 1998.jpg|thumb|Derek in 1998]]\nFollowing ''Ghosts Can\u2019t Do It'' Derek returned to acting in the television movies ''Hot Chocolate'' (1992) and ''Shattered Image'' (1994), and the straight-to-video film ''[[Woman of Desire]]'' (1994). In 1995 Derek appeared in the comedy film ''[[Tommy Boy]]''. For that performance Derek was nominated for a [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress]] but ultimately lost to [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] for the latter's performance in ''[[Four Rooms]]''.\n\nIn 1998 Derek guest-starred on four episodes of ''[[Wind on Water]].'' In 1999 she appeared on ''[[The Drew Carey Show]]'', and in the early 2000s she had guest roles on the shows ''[[Family Law (TV series)|Family Law]]'', ''[[Queen of Swords (TV series)|Queen of Swords]]'', ''[[Two Guys, a Girl and a Pizza Place]],'' ''[[Lucky (TV series)|Lucky]]'', ''[[Still Standing (TV series)|Still Standing]]'', and ''[[7th Heaven (TV series)|7th Heaven]]''.\n\nAt the [[20th Golden Raspberry Awards]] in 2000, Derek was nominated for Worst Actress of the Century, sharing the nomination with Madonna (the eventual winner), [[Brooke Shields]], [[Elizabeth Berkley]], and [[Pia Zadora]].\n\nDerek appeared in several more feature films during the 2000s, including ''[[Frozen with Fear]]'' (2000), ''[[The Master of Disguise]]'' (2002), for which she received her second [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress]] nomination, and ''[[Malibu's Most Wanted]]'' (2003). In 2006 Derek starred in 40 episodes of the 65-episode [[telenovela]] series ''[[Fashion House]]''. Derek had a featured role in the 2015 made-for-TV campy horror film ''[[Sharknado 3: Oh Hell No!]]''. Derek was reported to have participated in the 2016 [[Comedy Central]] [[roast (comedy)|roast]] of [[Rob Lowe]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2016/08/17/peyton-manning-bo-derek-comedy-central-roast-rob-lowe|title=Peyton Manning, Bo Derek, Rob Riggle set to roast Rob Lowe|publisher=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=19 August 2016}}</ref> but is absent from the eventual cast list.<ref>{{cite web|title=Comedy Central Roast of Rob Lowe|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6038506/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=2017-02-19}}</ref>\n\n=== Political ===\n\nDerek, who describes herself as [[Independent politician|independent]] with generally more [[libertarian]] views, supported [[George H.&nbsp;W. Bush]] in 1988 and 1992, and campaigned for his son [[George&nbsp;W. Bush]] in 2000 and 2004, and she appeared at both Republican conventions. In a January 2011 interview with ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'', she said she had voted for [[Barack Obama]] in 2008. She has appeared at events with bachelor Republican Congressman [[David Dreier]] of Southern California.<ref>[http://larryflynt.com/notebook.php?id=88 \"Congressman David Dreier: Gay & Ashamed\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051221182800/http://larryflynt.com/notebook.php?id=88 |date=December 21, 2005 }}, Larry Flynt.com</ref>\n\nWhen [[White House Chief of Staff]] [[Josh Bolten]] was asked about his relationship with Derek on the edition of April 30, 2006, of ''[[Fox News Sunday]]'' with [[Chris Wallace]], Bolten said she was a friend and a \"strong supporter of the President\".{{Citation needed|date=July 2013}} In 2006, she was appointed to the board of trustees of the [[John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts]] by President George W. Bush, on the operations committee.<ref>[http://www.kennedy-center.org/states/state.cfm?state=CA \"The Kennedy Center Activity Report for California\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080522084811/http://www.kennedy-center.org/states/state.cfm?state=CA |date=May 22, 2008 }} Kennedy Center web site</ref>\n\nIn 2012 Derek endorsed [[Mitt Romney]] for president.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/06/14/the-gop-s-two-faced-celeb-bashing-of-obama-s-parker-wintour-fundraiser.html|title=The GOP's Two-Faced Celeb Bashing of Obama's Parker-Wintour Fundraiser|first=Michelle|last=Cottle|date=June 14, 2012|work=[[The Daily Beast]] |accessdate=July 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\n=== Horse owner and activist ===\n\nA horse lover and riding enthusiast since childhood, Derek owns [[Andalusian horse]]s and is a spokesperson for the [[Animal Welfare Institute]]'s campaign to end horse slaughter through passage of federal and state legislation. On February 5, 2002, she published her autobiography entitled ''Riding Lessons: Everything That Matters in Life I Learned from Horses'' ({{ISBN|0-06-039437-4}}). She serves on the [[California Horse Racing Board]].\n\n=== Wounded veterans advocate ===\n\nDerek is a national honorary chairperson for [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs|Veterans Affairs]]' National Rehabilitation Special Events. She attended the 17th annual Disabled Veterans Winter Sports Clinic in [[Snowmass Village, Colorado]]. In 2003 she received the VA's highest honor from [[United States Secretary of Veterans Affairs|Secretary of Veterans Affairs]], [[Anthony Principi]]. Derek makes appearances on [[United Service Organizations]] tours. The [[Special Forces Association]] named her an honorary [[Special Forces (United States Army)|Green Beret]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www1.va.gov/opa/pressrel/pressrelease.cfm?id=698 |title = Bo Derek named honorary Green Beret |accessdate = January 18, 2008 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070813211713/http://www1.va.gov/opa/pressrel/pressrelease.cfm?id=698 |archive-date = August 13, 2007 |url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nDerek's father, Paul Collins, was a radio operator during the Korean war. Both her stepfather and late husband, John Derek, were veterans.\n\n=== Relationships ===\n\n[[File:Chandran Rutnam with John and Bo Derek.jpeg|thumb|right|Bo Derek with husband John Derek and [[Chandran Rutnam]]]]\n\nJohn and Bo moved to Germany and returned to the United States soon after Bo's 18th birthday; they married in 1976 and remained so until his death from heart failure in 1998.<ref>{{cite news |title = Obituary:John Derek |url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/obituary-john-derek-1157309.html |accessdate = January 15, 2012 |newspaper = The Independent |first = Tom |last = Vallance |date = May 25, 1998 }}</ref>\n\nSince 2002, she has been involved with actor [[John Corbett]].<ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1082778/Im-happy-says-Bo-Derek-opens-time-romance-Sex-And-The-Citys-John-Corbett.html 'I'm so happy', says Bo Derek as she opens up for the first time about romance with ''Sex and the City''{{'s}} John Corbett]</ref> She continues to live in California with her sister, brother-in-law, and their two children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebiographychannel.co.uk/biographies/bo-derek.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-02-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222162445/http://www.thebiographychannel.co.uk/biographies/bo-derek.html |archivedate=February 22, 2014 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n\n{{Anchor|Awards|Accolades}}\n* 1980 (Nominated): [[Golden Globe Award]] for Best New Star in ''10''\n* 1982 (Won): [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actress]] in ''Tarzan, the Ape Man''\n* 1985 (Won): Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actress in ''Bolero''\n* 1991 (Won): Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actress in ''Ghosts Can't Do It''\n* 1996 (Nominated): [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress]] in ''Tommy Boy''\n* 2000 (Nominated): Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actress of the Century in ''Tarzan, the Ape Man'', ''Bolero'', ''Ghosts Can't Do It'', etc.\n* 2002 (Nominated): Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress in ''The Master of Disguise''\n\n== Acting credits ==\n\n=== Film ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n| '''Film'''\n| '''Year'''\n| '''Role'''\n| '''Notes