here of the old Capitol Transit #20 trolley (Union Station to Cabin John) that was a very popular ride though the Palisades out to the Glen Echo Amusement Park (1898\u20131968).  In addition, the Georgetown Branch of the B & O railroad once worked its way through The Palisades, the most notable landmark being the steel trestle bridge over Arizona Ave.  Since the Georgetown Branch's abandonment in 1985, it has been part of the [[Capital Crescent Trail]].   \n\nThe [[Engine Company 29|Palisades Firehouse (Engine Company 29)]], at 4811 MacArthur Blvd. NW, built in 1925 is listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].  It was designed by architect [[Albert L. Harris]] in [[Colonial Revival architecture|Colonial Revival]] style. \n\nAlso National Register-listed are:\n*[[Conduit Road Schoolhouse]]\n*[[Dr. Franklin E. Kameny House]], ordinary-looking home of gay rights leader\n*[[Northwest No. 4 Boundary Marker of the Original District of Columbia]]\n*[[Washington Aqueduct]].\n\nDesigned by John J. Zink, the MacArthur Theater, originally a single 1,000 seater that was tri-plexed in 1982, was in use from December 1946 through March 1997.\n\nOn September 11, 1936, at a cost of $40,000, the Palisades Playground and field house was dedicated at its current Sherier and Edmunds Place location.\n\nThe Palisades neighborhood is the home for a variety of popular restaurants such as Figs, Makoto, Bambu, Bistro Aracosia, BlackSalt, Chen's Gourmet, Seventh Hill Pizza, Kotobuki, DC Boathouse, Et Voila' and the new Salt and Pepper Restaurant, and its very own pet supply store, Profeed of DC.\n\nA high point of the year for many in the neighborhood is the annual July 4 parade, featuring local bands, fire engines and children on highly decorated tricycles and bicycles.\n\n==Education==\n[[District of Columbia Public Schools]] operates public schools. Mann Elementary School, Key Elementary School, [[Hardy Middle School (Washington, D.C.)|Hardy Middle School]], and [[Woodrow Wilson High School (Washington, D.C.)|Wilson High School]] serve Palisades.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/special/local/dc-school-zones/</ref>\n\nPrivate schools in Palisades include Our Lady of Victory Catholic School, [[Lab School of Washington|the Lab School]], the lower and middle divisions of [[Georgetown Day School]], the River School, and St. Patrick's Episcopal Day School.<ref>http://www.palisadesdc.org/schools.php</ref>\n\n[[District of Columbia Public Library]] operates the Palisades Neighborhood Library.<ref>\"[http://www.dclibrary.org/hours-locations Hours & Locations].\" [[District of Columbia Public Library]]. Retrieved on October 21, 2009.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons cat|The Palisades, Washington, D.C.}}\n*[http://www.palisadesdc.org/ Palisades' Citizens Association]\n*[http://ghostsofdc.org/2012/02/04/palisades-of-the-potomac-1890/ Palisades of the Potomac (1890)]\n\n{{Neighborhoods in Washington, D.C.}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Palisades, The, Washington, D.C.}}\n[[Category:1893 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:American upper class]]\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Northwest (Washington, D.C.)]]\n[[Category:The Palisades (Washington, D.C.)| ]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo: though\u2192through", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Palisades_(Washington,_D.C.)"}
{"title_page": "Maude Adams", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{About|the American stage actress|the Swedish actress and model|Maud Adams}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                    = Maude Adams\n| image                   = Maude Adams1.jpg\n| caption                 = Maude Adams, 1901\n| birth_name              = Maude Ewing Adams Kiskadden\n| birth_date              = {{Birth date|1872|11|11}}\n| birth_place             = [[Salt Lake City, Utah]], U.S.\n| death_date              = {{Death date and age|1953|07|17|1872|11|1}}\n| death_place             = [[Tannersville, New York]], U.S.\n| occupation              = Actress\n| years_active            = 1880\u20131918, 1931\u20131934    \n| signature               = Maude Adams signature.svg}}\n\n'''Maude Ewing Adams Kiskadden''' (November 11, 1872 \u2013 July 17, 1953), known professionally as '''Maude Adams''', was an American actress who achieved her greatest success as the character [[Peter Pan]], first playing the role in the 1905 [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production of ''[[Peter and Wendy|Peter Pan; or, The Boy Who Wouldn't Grow Up]]''.<ref name=Patterson>{{cite book  |last=Patterson |first=Ada |authorlink=Ada Patterson| url=http://www.ldsfilm.com/actors/MaudeAdamsBio.html| title=Maude Adams: A Biography |year=1907|accessdate=22 April 2011}}</ref> Adams's personality appealed to a large audience and helped her become the most successful and highest-paid performer of her day, with a yearly income of more than one million dollars during her peak.<ref name=Patterson/><ref name=\"trivia-library.com\">{{cite web| url=http://www.trivia-library.com/a/famous-stage-actress-biography-of-maude-adams.htm|title=Famous Stage Actress Biography of Maude Adams}}</ref>\n\nAdams began performing as a child while accompanying her actress mother on tour.  At age 16, she made her Broadway debut, and under [[Charles Frohman]]'s management, she became a popular player alongside leading man [[John Drew Jr.]] in the early 1890s. Beginning in 1897, Adams starred in plays by [[J. M. Barrie]], including ''The Little Minister'', ''[[Quality Street (play)|Quality Street]]'', ''[[What Every Woman Knows (play)|What Every Woman Knows]]'' and ''Peter Pan''. These productions made Adams the most popular actress in America.<ref>Marcosson and Frohman, p. 175</ref> She also performed in various other plays. Her last Broadway play, in 1916, was Barrie's ''[[A Kiss for Cinderella]]''. After a 13-year retirement, she appeared in more Shakespeare plays and then taught acting in Missouri. She then retired to upstate New York.\n\n==Early life and career==\n[[File:Maude Adams age 1880.jpg|thumb|left|Adams (left) and Flora Walsh<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/83964590/flora-hoyt Flora Walsh; findagrave.com]</ref> in ''The Wandering Boys'' in [[San Francisco]], 1880]]\nAdams was born in [[Salt Lake City]], Utah, the daughter of [[Annie Adams|Asaneth Ann \"Annie\"]] ([[Maiden and married names|n\u00e9e]] Adams) and James Henry Kiskadden. Adams' mother was an actress, and her father had jobs working for a bank and in a mine.<ref name=Utah>{{citation|first=Ann W.|last=Engar|contribution=Adams, Maude|contribution-url=http://www.uen.org/utah_history_encyclopedia/a/Adams_Maude.html| editor-last=Powell| editor-first=Allan Kent|year=1994|title=Utah History Encyclopedia|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|publisher= [[University of Utah Press]]|isbn=0874804256|oclc=30473917}}</ref> Little else is known of Adams's father, who died when she was young.<ref>The 1870 Utah census lists James H. Kiskadden as the head of a household that included his wife Lucina and several younger Adams', perhaps siblings of Lucina. James reported his birthplace as Ohio. The 1880 California census reports James Kisskaden (age 48), Anne Kisskaden (age 29) and Maude Kisskaden (age 7) living in San Francisco. The latter two list their birthplace as Utah.</ref> James was not a [[Mormons|Mormon]], and Adams once wrote of her father as having been a \"gentile\". The surname \"Kiskadden\" is [[Scottish people|Scottish]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.houseofnames.com/xq/asp.c/qx/Kiscadden-coat-arms.htm?a=54323-224 |title=Kiskadden Coat of Arms |publisher=Houseofnames.com |date=2003-10-02 |access-date=2014-02-07 }}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On her mother's side, Adams' great grandfather Platt Banker converted to [[Mormonism]] and moved his family to [[Missouri]], where his daughter Julia married Barnabus Adams. Barnabus and Julia then migrated as part of [[Mormon_pioneers#Vanguard_company_of_1847|the first company]] to enter the [[Salt Lake Valley]] with [[Brigham Young]] in 1847, where he cut timbers for the [[Salt Lake Tabernacle]].<ref name=RSobit>Cannon, Ramona W. [https://archive.org/details/reliefsocietymag1953reli/page/594 \"Woman's Sphere\"], ''[[Relief Society Magazine]]'', September 1953, Vol 40, no. 9, p. 595</ref> Adams was also a descendant of ''Mayflower'' passenger [[John Howland]].<ref name=GBR500>{{Citation| last = Roberts| first = Gary Boyd| author-link = Gary Boyd Roberts| title = The Mayflower 500| publisher = New England Historic Genealogical Society| publication-date = 2020| isbn = 978-0-88082-397-5| page = 268}}</ref>\n\nAdams appeared on stage at two months old in the play ''The Lost Baby'' at the Salt Lake City Brigham Young Theatre.<ref name=\"Women of Character\">{{cite book|last1=Black|first1=Susan Easton| last2=Woodger| first2=Mary Jane| title=Women of Character|date=2011|publisher=Covenant Communications, Inc.|location=American Fork, UT|isbn=978-1-60861-212-3| pages=1\u20133}}</ref> She appeared again at the age of nine months in her mother's arms. Over her father's objections, Adams began acting as a small child, adopting her mother's maiden name as her stage name. They toured throughout the western U.S. with a theatrical troupe that played in rural areas, mining towns and some cities.<ref name=Utah/> At the age of five, Adams starred in a [[San Francisco]] theater as \"Little Schneider\" in ''Fritz, Our German Cousin'' and as \"Adrienne Renaud\" in ''A Celebrated Case''.<ref name=\"trivia-library.com\"/> At the age of nine, Adams lived with her Mormon grandmother and Mormon cousins in Salt Lake City, while her mother remained in San Francisco.<ref name=Mormons>{{cite book| last1=Hunter| first1=J. Michael|title=Mormons and Popular Culture: The Global Influence of an American Phenomenon|date=2013| publisher=Praeger| location=Santa Barbara| isbn=9780313391675| pages=135\u2013139|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171120162802/https://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2390&context=facpub| chapter=Maude Adams and the Mormons| archive-date=20 November 2017|url=https://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2390&context=facpub}}</ref> It is not clear whether she identified as a member of [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] as her mother did. She was never baptized Presbyterian, although she attended a Presbyterian school.<ref name=Mormons/> Later in life, Adams took long sabbaticals in Catholic convents, and in 1922 she donated her estates at [[Lake Ronkonkoma, New York]], to the [[Sisters of the Cenacle]], for use as a novitiate and retreat house.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.lakeronkonkomacivic.org/ronkonkoma/ronkonkoma.html |title=Lake Ronkonkoma History, Legends & Myths |url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100204081238/http://www.lakeronkonkomacivic.org/ronkonkoma/ronkonkoma.html |archivedate=2010-02-04 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.lakerhs.org/rhs/our%20town.htm#myths | title=Lake Ronkonkoma Historical Society | access-date=2017-03-31}}</ref> She never converted to Catholicism or discussed the topic in any interviews.<ref name=Mormons/>\n\nAdams debuted in New York at age ten in ''Esmeralda'' and then returned briefly to California. She then returned to Salt Lake City to live with her grandmother and studied at the Salt Lake Collegiate Institute.<ref name=Utah/> She later wrote of Salt Lake City, \"The people of the valley have gentle manners, as if their spirits moved with dignity.\"<ref name=RSobit/> Adams also later wrote a short essay, \"The One I Knew Least\", where she described her difficulty in discovering her own personality while playing so many theatrical roles as a child.<ref name=Utah/>\n\n==Early adult career==\n[[File:Adams Peter Pan.jpg|thumb|Adams as [[Peter Pan]]]]\nAdams returned to New York City at age 16 to appear in ''[[The Paymaster]]''.  She then became a member of [[E. H. Sothern]]'s theatre company in Boston, appearing in ''The Highest Bidder'', and then was on Broadway in ''[[Lord Chumley]]'' in 1888. [[Charles H. Hoyt]] then cast her in ''[[A Midnight Bell (play)|A Midnight Bell]]'' where audiences, if not the critics, took notice of her.  In 1889, sensing he had a potential new star on his hands, Hoyt offered her a five-year contract, but Adams declined in favor of a lesser offer from the powerful producer [[Charles Frohman]] who, from that point forward, took control of her career.  She soon left behind juvenile parts and began to play leading roles for Frohman,<ref name=Utah/> often alongside her mother.<ref>[http://www.ibdb.com/Person/View/29322 \"Annie Adams\"], [[Internet Broadway Database]], accessed January 20, 2016</ref> In 1890, Frohman asked [[David Belasco]] and [[Henry Churchill de Mille|Henry C. de Mille]] to specially write the part of Dora Prescott for Adams in their new play ''[[Men and Women (play)|Men and Women]]'', which Frohman was producing. The next year, she appeared as Nell in ''The Lost Paradise''.\n\nIn 1892, [[John Drew Jr.]] (one of the leading stars of the day) ended his 18-year association with [[Augustin Daly]] and joined Frohman's company. Frohman paired Adams and Drew in a series of plays beginning with ''[[The Masked Ball]]'' and ending with ''[[Rosemary (play)|Rosemary]]'' in 1896. She then spent five years as the leading lady in John Drew's company.<ref name=\"cp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.collectorspost.com/cgi-bin/ShopLoader.cgi?Actors/maude_adams.html|title=Maude Adams|publisher=Collectors Post|accessdate=2006-11-02}}</ref> There, \"her work was praised for its charm, delicacy, and simplicity.\"<ref name=Utah/> ''The Masked Ball'' opened on October 8, 1892.  Audiences came to see its star, Drew, but left remembering Adams. Most memorable was a scene in which her character feigned tipsiness for which she received a two-minute ovation on opening night. Drew was the star, but it was for Adams that the audience gave twelve curtain calls, and previously tepid critics gave generous reviews. ''Harpers Weekly'' wrote: \"It is difficult to see just who is going to prevent Miss Adams from becoming the leading exponent of light comedy in America.  ''The New York Times'' wrote that Adams, \"not John Drew, has made the success of ''The Masked Ball'' at Palmer's, and is the star of the comedy. Manager Charles Frohman, in attempting to exploit one star, has happened upon another of greater magnitude.\" The tipsy scene started Adams on her path to being a favorite among New York audiences and led to an eighteen-month run for the play.\n\nLess successful plays followed, including ''[[The Butterflies (play)|The Butterflies]]'', ''[[The Bauble Shop]]'', ''[[Christopher, Jr.]]'', ''[[The Imprudent Young Couple]]'' and ''[[The Squire of Dames]]''. But 1896 saw an upturn for Adams with ''Rosemary''. A comedy about the failed elopement of a young couple, sheltered for the night by an older man (Drew), the play received critical praise and box office success.<ref name=\"manybooks.net\">{{cite web|url=http://manybooks.net/pages/marcossoni2614626146-8/128.html|title=Charles Frohman: Manager and Man pr 128}}</ref>\n\n==Barrie and Stardom==\n[[File:The-Little-Minister-1897.jpg|thumb|left|Adams and [[Robert Edeson]] in the Broadway production of ''The Little Minister'' (1897)]]\n[[File:Maude Adams in The Little Minister.jpg|thumb|upright|Poster for ''The Little Minister'' (1897)]]\n[[File:Mucha-Maud Adams as Joan of Arc-1909.jpg|thumb|upright|Adams as [[Joan of Arc]], painted by [[Alphonse Mucha]] (1909)]]\nFrohman had been pursuing [[J. M. Barrie]] (the future author of ''[[Peter and Wendy|Peter Pan]]'') to adapt the author's popular book ''The Little Minister'' into a play, but Barrie had resisted because he felt there was no actress who could play Lady Babbie. On a trip to New York in 1896, Barrie attended a performance of ''Rosemary'' and at once decided that Adams was the actress to play Lady Babbie.<ref name=\"manybooks.net\"/><ref name=Famous1>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/famousamericanac007101mbp/famousamericanac007101mbp_djvu.txt|title=Famous American Actors and Actresses, p. 92}}</ref> Frohman worried that the masculine aspects of the book might overshadow Adams's role. With Barrie's consent, several key scenes were changed to favor Lady Babbie.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://manybooks.net/pages/marcossoni2614626146-8/129.html|title=Charles Frohman: Manager and Man pr 129}}</ref> The play opened in 1897 at the [[Empire Theatre (41st Street)|Empire Theatre]] and was a tremendous success, running for 300 performances in New York (289 of which were standing room only) and setting a new all time box office record of $370,000; it made Adams a star.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://manybooks.net/pages/marcossoni2614626146-8/131.html|title=Charles Frohman: Manager and Man pr 131}}</ref><ref name=Famous1/> It also toured successfully, running for 65 performances in Boston.<ref name=Utah/>\n\nAnother play by Barrie, ''[[Peter and Wendy|Peter Pan; or, The Boy Who Wouldn't Grow Up]]'' (1904), became the role with which Adams was most closely identified.  She was the first actress to play [[Peter Pan]] on Broadway. Only days after her casting was announced, Adams had an emergency appendectomy, and it was uncertain whether her health would allow her to assume the role as planned. ''Peter Pan'' opened on October 16, 1905 at the [[National Theatre (Washington, D.C.)|National Theatre]] in Washington, D.C. to little success.<ref>{{cite book|last=Fields|first=Armond|title=Maude Adams|year=2004|publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc.|location=North Carolina|isbn=0-7864-1927-X|page=184}}</ref>  It soon moved to Broadway, where the play had a long run.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=. https://www.loc.gov/resource/sn83030313/1906-03-31/ed-1/?sp=19&q=Maude+Adams+Peter+Pan&r=0.434,0.034,0.641,0.23,0.|title=\"Charles Frohman's Leading Theatres\"|date=March 31, 1906|work=The New York Herald|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Adams appeared in the role on Broadway several times over the following decade.{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}} The collar of her 1905 Peter Pan costume, which she had co-designed, was an immediate fashion success and was henceforth known as the\n\n\"[[Peter Pan collar]]\".<ref name=\"Felsenthal\">{{cite news|last=Felsenthal|first=Julia|title=Where the Peter Pan Collar Came From\u2014and Why It's Back|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2012/01/20/peter_pan_collar_where_it_came_from_and_why_it_s_back.html| accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=[[Slate Magazine]]|date=20 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nAdams starred in other works by Barrie, including ''[[Quality Street (play)|Quality Street]]'' (1901), ''[[What Every Woman Knows (play)|What Every Woman Knows]]'' (1908), ''[[The Legend of Leonora]]'' (1914), ''[[A Kiss for Cinderella]]'' (1916).  However, she also appeared in other works. In 1899, she portrayed Shakespeare's Juliet.  She was a thin twenty-four year old playing the adolescent Juliet. While audiences praised her with standing ovations, critics generally disliked it. The critic, Alan Dale, reviewed her performance in one column about her debut as Juliet at the Empire Theatre with a mixture of admiration and criticism. He called her Elizabethan English \"grotesque at times.\"  Then noted Adams had performed with \"pretty purring,\" not classical. On the other hand, he described her as thin and her performance as \"romantic,\"  \"sublime,\"  as \"not sinking beneath the waves.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dale|first=Alan|url=https://www.loc.gov/resource/sn83030180/1899-05-09/ed-1/?sp=3&q=Maude+Adams+Romeo+and+Juliet&r=-0.042,0.414,0.636,0.228,0|title=Alan Dale Reviews the Performance.|date=May 9, 1899|work=The New York Journal and Advertiser|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> While audiences loved her in the role,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Eldridge|first=\"Aunt Louisa\"|url=https://www.loc.gov/resource/sn83030180/1899-05-09/ed-1/?sp=3&q=Maude+Adams+Romeo+and+Juliet&r=0.258,0.169,0.474,0.17,0|title=\"Twelve Times the Curtain Rose\"|date=May 9, 1899|work=The New York Journal and Advertiser|access-date=April 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> selling out the sixteen performances in New York, the critics disliked it.{{citation needed|date=October 2013}}  ''[[Romeo and Juliet]]'' was followed by ''[[L'Aiglon]]'' in 1900, a French play about the life of [[Napoleon II of France]] in which Adams played the leading role, foreshadowing her portrayal of another male (Peter Pan) five years later.  The play had starred [[Sarah Bernhardt]] in Paris with enthusiastic reviews, but Adams's ''L'Aiglon'' received mixed reviews in New York. In 1909, she played Joan of Arc in [[Friedrich Schiller]]'s ''[[The Maid of Orleans (play)|The Maid of Orleans]]''.  This was produced on a huge scale at the [[Harvard University]] Stadium by Frohman.<ref>\"Maude Adams in a Rehearsal of \"Joan of Arc\" at the Stadium. ''[[The New York Times]]'', May 30, 1909</ref> The June 24, 1909 edition of the ''Paducah Evening Sun'' (Kentucky) contains the following excerpt:\n\n<blockquote>Joan at Harvard, Schiller's Play reproduced on Gigantic scale. \u2026 The experiment of producing Schiller's \"Maid of Orleans\" beneath starry skies \u2026 was carried out \u2026 by ... Adams and a company numbering about two thousand persons \u2026 at the Harvard Stadium. \u2026  A special electric light plant was installed \u2026 a great cathedral was erected, background constructed and a realistic forest created. \u2026  Miss Adams was accorded an ovation at the end of the performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85052114/1909-06-24/ed-1/seq-2/ |title='&#39;The Paducah Evening Sun'&#39; excerpt (06/24/1909) |publisher=Chroniclingamerica.loc.gov |date=1909-06-24 |accessdate=2014-02-07}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nShe appeared in another French play with 1911's ''[[Chantecler (play)|Chantecler]]'', the story of a rooster who believes his crowing makes the sun rise.<ref name=\"Broadway by Ken Bloom pg 8\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rqi3d1925IcC&pg=PA51&lpg=PA51&dq=Ethel+Barrymore+understudy+Maude+Adams&source=web&ots=cb-hQJxt_Q&sig=7Zxwx5h_cpnU6i6o4y2-f2xTYYI&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=1&ct=result#PPA8,M1|title=Broadway by Ken Bloom pg 8}}</ref> She fared only slightly better than in ''L'Aiglon'' with the critics, but audiences again embraced her, on one occasion giving her twenty two curtain calls.<ref name=\"Broadway by Ken Bloom pg 8\"/> Adams later cited it as her favorite role, with Peter Pan a close second.\n\n==Retirement and death==\nAdams retired in 1918 after a severe bout of [[influenza]].<ref name=\"harbin\">{{Cite book |title=The Gay & Lesbian Theatrical Legacy: A Biographical Dictionary of Major Figures in American Stage History in the Pre-Stonewall Era |year=2005 |publisher=University of Michigan Press |pages=16\u201318 |editor-last=Harbin |editor-first=Billy J. |editor2-last=Marra |editor2-first=Kim |editor3-last=Schanke |editor3-first=Robert A. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f0fbSlGN8uUC&pg=PA16}}</ref> Her lights ultimately became the industry standard in Hollywood with the advent of sound in motion pictures in the late 1920s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utahwomenshistory.org/bios/maude-adams/|title=Maude Adams|website=Better Days Curriculum|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>  During the 1920s, she worked with [[General Electric]] to develop improved and more powerful stage lighting and with the Eastman Company in developing color photography.  It has been suggested that her motivation for her association with these technology companies was because she wished to appear in a color film version of ''Peter Pan'', and this would have required better lighting and techniques for color photography.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trivia-library.com/a/famous-stage-actress-biography-of-maude-adams.htm |title=Trivia on Famous Stage Actress Biography of Maude Adams |publisher=Trivia Library |date= |accessdate=2014-02-07}}</ref>  After 13 years away from the stage, she returned to acting, appearing occasionally in regional productions of [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]] plays, including as Portia in ''[[The Merchant of Venice]]'' in Ohio, in 1931, and as Maria in ''[[Twelfth Night]]'' in 1934 in Maine.<ref name=Utah/>\n\nOften described as shy, Adams was referred to by [[Ethel Barrymore]] as the \"original [[Greta Garbo#Public persona|'I want to be alone' woman]]\".<ref>{{Cite book |title=The Great White Way: a re-creation of Broadway's golden era of theatrical entertainment |page=107 |year=1962 |publisher=Dutton |first=Allen |last=Churchill}}</ref> Her retiring lifestyle, including the absence of any relationships with men, contributed to the virtuous and innocent public image promoted by Frohman and was reflected in her most successful roles. Biographers have concluded that Adams was a lesbian.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Fd7BAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA114 |title=Making American Culture |first=Patricia |last=Bradley |year=2009 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Madsen| first1=Axel| title=The Sewing Circle: Sappho's Leading Ladies|date=February 2002|publisher=Kensington Publishing Corporation|location=New York City|isbn=978-0758201010|page=3| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QwxFfhiFcAAC&lpg=PA243&pg=PA3}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Schanke|first1=Robert A.|title=That Furious Lesbian: The Story of Mercedes de Acosta|date=10 May 2004| publisher=Southern Illinois University Press| isbn=0809325799|page=14|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LesZDgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA14&pg=PA14}}</ref> She had two long-term relationships that only ended upon her partners' deaths: Lillie Florence, from the early 1890s until 1901, and Louise Boynton (1858\u20131951) from 1905 until 1951.<ref name=\"harbin\"/><ref name=\"Legacy\">{{cite book|last1=Harbin|first1=Billy J.|last2=Marra|first2=Kimberley Bell|last3=Schanke|first3=Robert A.|title=The Gay and Lesbian Theatrical Legacy: A Biographical Dictionary of Major Figures in American Stage History in the Pre-Stonewall Era|date=28 March 2007|publisher=University of Michigan Press|isbn=978-0472068586|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f0fbSlGN8uUC&lpg=PA18&ots=lKK89j4hPP&pg=PA15}}</ref>{{rp|16}} She is supposed to have had a romantic relationship with actress [[Spring Byington]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bendix|first1=Trish|title=The Gay Women of Old Hollywood|url=http://www.newnownext.com/the-gay-women-of-old-hollywood/09/2010| website=newnownext.com| publisher=Viacom International Inc.|date=1 September 2010}}</ref> Adams was known at times to supplement the salaries of fellow performers out of her own pay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utahwomenshistory.org/bios/maude-adams/|title=Maude Adams|website=Better Days Curriculum|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Once while touring, a theater owner significantly raised the price of tickets, knowing Adams's name meant a sold-out house. Adams made the owner refund the difference before she appeared on the stage that night.<ref>Robbins (1956), p. 219</ref> Adams was the head of the drama department at [[Stephens College]] in Missouri from 1937 to 1949, becoming known as an inspiring teacher in the arts of acting.<ref name=\"cp\"/><ref>Fields, p. 299</ref>\n\nAfter her retirement, Adams was on occasion pursued for roles in film. The closest she came to accepting was in 1938, when producer David O. Selznick persuaded her to do a screen test (with [[Janet Gaynor]], who would later play the female lead) for the role of Miss Fortune in the film ''[[The Young in Heart]]''. After negotiations failed, the role was played by [[Minnie Dupree]]. The twelve-minute screen test was preserved by the George Eastman House in 2004.<ref name=\"bampfa preserved\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bampfa.berkeley.edu/event/young-heart-0 |title=The Young in Heart |publisher=[[Berkeley Art Museum and Pacific Film Archive]] |accessdate=April 21, 2017 |archivedate=April 22, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170422135937/http://www.bampfa.berkeley.edu/event/young-heart-0 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nShe died, aged 80, at her summer home, Caddam Hill, in [[Tannersville, New York]], and is interred in the cemetery of the [[Sisters of the Cenacle]], [[Lake Ronkonkoma, New York]]<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.lioddities.com/Maude%20Adams/MaudeAdams.htm| title=Long Island Oddities| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080915021200/http://www.lioddities.com/Maude%20Adams/MaudeAdams.htm| archivedate=2008-09-15}}</ref> and Louise Boynton is buried alongside her.<ref>Wilson, Scott. ''Resting Places: The Burial Sites of More Than 14,000 Famous Persons'', 3d ed.: 2. McFarland & Company (2016) {{ISBN|0786479922}} In 1898, Adams purchased a farm in Lake Ronkonkoma called Sandy Garth, which in 1922 she donated to the Sisters of St. Regis, and had the Cenacle Retreat House built for them. See {{Cite book |title=Images of America: Lake Ronkonkoma |page=88 |year=2011 |publisher=Arcadia Publishing |first=Keith |last=Oswald |first2=Dale |last2=Spencer}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe character of Elise McKenna in [[Richard Matheson]]'s 1975 novel ''[[Bid Time Return]]'' and its 1980 film adaptation, ''[[Somewhere in Time (film)|Somewhere in Time]]'', in which the character was played by [[Jane Seymour (actress)|Jane Seymour]], was based on Maude Adams.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/600137031/Legendary-sci-fi-author-tackles-social-commentary.html?pg=all|title=Legendary sci-fi author tackles social commentary|work=Deseret News|date=2005-05-29|accessdate=2014-04-07}}</ref> In the novel, Elise is appearing in ''The Little Minister'', which role was also said to have been written especially for her. {{citation needed|date=December 2009}}\n[[File:Maude Adams as Phoebe in Quality Street.jpg|thumb|upright|Adams as Phoebe in ''[[Quality Street (play)|Quality Street]]'' (1901)]]\n\n==Broadway appearances==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[The Paymaster]]'' \u2013 1888\n* ''[[Lord Chumley]]'' \u2013 1888\n* ''[[A Midnight Bell (play)|A Midnight Bell]]'' \u2013 1889\n* ''[[Men and Women (play)|Men and Women]]'' \u2013 1890\n* ''[[The Masked Ball]]'' \u2013 1892\n* ''[[The Butterflies (play)|The Butterflies]]'' \u2013 1894\n* ''[[The Bauble Shop]]'' \u2013 1894\n* ''[[The Imprudent Young Couple]]'' \u2013 1895\n* ''[[Christopher, Jr.]]'' \u2013 1895\n* ''[[The Squire of Dames]]'' \u2013 1896\n* ''[[Rosemary (play)|Rosemary]]'' \u2013 1896\n* ''The Little Minister'' \u2013 1897 and 1904\n* ''[[Romeo and Juliet]]'' \u2013 1899\n* ''[[L'Aiglon (play)|L'Aiglon]]'' \u2013 1900\n* ''[[Quality Street (play)|Quality Street]]'' \u2013 1901\n* ''[[The Pretty Sister of Jose]]'' \u2013 1903\n* ''[['Op o' Me Thumb]]'' \u2013 1905\n* ''[[Peter Pan]]'' \u2013 1905, 1906, 1912 and 1915\n* ''[[Quality Street (play)|Quality Street]]'' \u2013 1908\n* ''The Jesters'' \u2013 1908\n* ''[[The-Merry-Go-Round]]'' \u2013 1908\n* ''[[What Every Woman Knows (play)|What Every Woman Knows]]'' \u2013 1908\n* ''[[Chantecler (play)|Chantecler]]'' \u2013 1911\n* ''[[The Legend of Leonora]]'' \u2013 1914\n* ''The Little Minister'' \u2013 1916\n* ''[[A Kiss for Cinderella]]'' \u2013 1916\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uw5HrxKyIR4C&dq=Christopher,+Jr.++Maude+Adams&source=gbs_navlinks_s| title=Maude Adams: Idol of American Theater, 1872-1953| author=[[Armond Fields]]| publisher=McFarland| year=2004|isbn=978-0-7864-1927-2}}\n* {{Cite book| last1 = Marcosson| first1 = Isaac Frederick| authorlink=Isaac Frederick Marcosson| last2 = Frohman| first2 = Daniel| title = Charles Frohman: Manager and Man| publisher = John Lane, The Bodley Head| url=https://archive.org/details/charlesfrohmanma00marc| date = 1916}}\n*Robbins, Phyllis. ''Maude Adams: An Intimate Portrait'' (1956)\n*Robbins, Phyllis. ''The Young Maude Adams'' (1959)\n* {{citation|last=Stern|first=Keith|chapter=Maude Adams|title=Queers in History|publisher=BenBella Books, Inc.; Dallas, Texas|year=2009|isbn=978-1-933771-87-8}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography|LGBT}}\n{{commons category|Maude Adams}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{IMDb name|5155958}}\n* {{NYPL Digital Gallery keyword|Maude Adams}} held by the Billy Rose Theatre Division, [[New York Public Library for the Performing Arts]]\n* [http://archives.nypl.org/the/21337 Maude Adams collection, 1879-1956], held by the Billy Rose Theatre Division, [[New York Public Library for the Performing Arts]]\n* {{Find a Grave|8}}\n*[https://archive.today/20130131040538/http://www.periodpaper.com/index.php/1910-maude-adams-actress-peter-pan-will-bradley-print Maude Adams; PeriodPaper.com c. 1910]\n* [http://www.booklibris.com/MaudeAdamsBiographiesList.htm Maude Adams profile and list of biographies]\n* [http://gutenberg.org/files/57611/57611-h/57611-h.htm Heroines of The Modern Stage] p.324 by Forrest Izard c.1915\n*[https://www.utahwomenshistory.org/bios/maude-adams/ Maude Adams]at [https://www.betterdays2020.com/ Better Days 2020, Key Players.]2017.{{Wikisource-inline|list=\n** {{Cite NIE|wstitle=Adams, Maude Kiskadden|year=1905|short=x |noicon=x}}\n** {{Cite Americana|wstitle=Adams, Maud Kiskadden|year=1920 |short=x |noicon=x}}\n** {{Cite Collier's|wstitle=Adams, Maude Kiskadden|year=1921|short=x |noicon=x}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adams, Maude}}\n[[Category:1872 births]]\n[[Category:1953 deaths]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:19th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Lesbian actresses]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Utah]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Salt Lake City]]\n[[Category:Stephens College faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{About|the American stage actress|the Swedish actress and model|Maud Adams}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                    = Maude Adams\n| image                   = Maude Adams1.jpg\n| caption                 = Maude Adams, 1901\n| birth_name              = Maude Ewing Adams Kiskadden\n| birth_date              = {{Birth date|1872|11|11}}\n| birth_place             = [[Salt Lake City, Utah]], U.S.\n| death_date              = {{Death date and age|1953|07|17|1872|11|1}}\n| death_place             = [[Tannersville, New York]], U.S.\n| occupation              = Actress\n| years_active            = 1880\u20131918, 1931\u20131934    \n| signature               = Maude Adams signature.svg}}\n\n'''Maude Ewing Adams Kiskadden''' (November 11, 1872 \u2013 July 17, 1953), known professionally as '''Maude Adams''', was an American actress who achieved her greatest success as the character [[Peter Pan]], first playing the role in the 1905 [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production of ''[[Peter and Wendy|Peter Pan; or, The Boy Who Wouldn't Grow Up]]''.<ref name=Patterson>{{cite book  |last=Patterson |first=Ada |authorlink=Ada Patterson| url=http://www.ldsfilm.com/actors/MaudeAdamsBio.html| title=Maude Adams: A Biography |year=1907|accessdate=22 April 2011}}</ref> Adams's personality appealed to a large audience and helped her become the most successful and highest-paid performer of her day, with a yearly income of more than one million dollars during her peak.<ref name=Patterson/><ref name=\"trivia-library.com\">{{cite web| url=http://www.trivia-library.com/a/famous-stage-actress-biography-of-maude-adams.htm|title=Famous Stage Actress Biography of Maude Adams}}</ref>\n\nAdams began performing as a child while accompanying her actress mother on tour.  At age 16, she made her Broadway debut, and under [[Charles Frohman]]'s management, she became a popular player alongside leading man [[John Drew Jr.]] in the early 1890s. Beginning in 1897, Adams starred in plays by [[J. M. Barrie]], including ''The Little Minister'', ''[[Quality Street (play)|Quality Street]]'', ''[[What Every Woman Knows (play)|What Every Woman Knows]]'' and ''Peter Pan''. These productions made Adams the most popular actress in America.<ref>Marcosson and Frohman, p. 175</ref> She also performed in various other plays. Her last Broadway play, in 1916, was Barrie's ''[[A Kiss for Cinderella]]''. After a 13-year retirement, she appeared in more Shakespeare plays and then taught acting in Missouri. She then retired to upstate New York.\n\n==Early life and career==\n[[File:Maude Adams age 1880.jpg|thumb|left|Adams (left) and Flora Walsh<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/83964590/flora-hoyt Flora Walsh; findagrave.com]</ref> in ''The Wandering Boys'' in [[San Francisco]], 1880]]\nAdams was born in [[Salt Lake City]], Utah, the daughter of [[Annie Adams|Asaneth Ann \"Annie\"]] ([[Maiden and married names|n\u00e9e]] Adams) and James Henry Kiskadden. Adams' mother was an actress, and her father had jobs working for a bank and in a mine.<ref name=Utah>{{citation|first=Ann W.|last=Engar|contribution=Adams, Maude|contribution-url=http://www.uen.org/utah_history_encyclopedia/a/Adams_Maude.html| editor-last=Powell| editor-first=Allan Kent|year=1994|title=Utah History Encyclopedia|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|publisher= [[University of Utah Press]]|isbn=0874804256|oclc=30473917}}</ref> Little else is known of Adams's father, who died when she was young.<ref>The 1870 Utah census lists James H. Kiskadden as the head of a household that included his wife Lucina and several younger Adams', perhaps siblings of Lucina. James reported his birthplace as Ohio. The 1880 California census reports James Kisskaden (age 48), Anne Kisskaden (age 29) and Maude Kisskaden (age 7) living in San Francisco. The latter two list their birthplace as Utah.</ref> James was not a [[Mormons|Mormon]], and Adams once wrote of her father as having been a \"gentile\". The surname \"Kiskadden\" is [[Scottish people|Scottish]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.houseofnames.com/xq/asp.c/qx/Kiscadden-coat-arms.htm?a=54323-224 |title=Kiskadden Coat of Arms |publisher=Houseofnames.com |date=2003-10-02 |access-date=2014-02-07 }}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On her mother's side, Adams' great grandfather Platt Banker converted to [[Mormonism]] and moved his family to [[Missouri]], where his daughter Julia married Barnabus Adams. Barnabus and Julia then migrated as part of [[Mormon_pioneers#Vanguard_company_of_1847|the first company]] to enter the [[Salt Lake Valley]] with [[Brigham Young]] in 1847, where he cut timbers for the [[Salt Lake Tabernacle]].<ref name=RSobit>Cannon, Ramona W. [https://archive.org/details/reliefsocietymag1953reli/page/594 \"Woman's Sphere\"], ''[[Relief Society Magazine]]'', September 1953, Vol 40, no. 9, p. 595</ref> Adams was also a descendant of ''Mayflower'' passenger [[John Howland]].<ref name=GBR500>{{Citation| last = Roberts| first = Gary Boyd| author-link = Gary Boyd Roberts| title = The Mayflower 500| publisher = New England Historic Genealogical Society| publication-date = 2020| isbn = 978-0-88082-397-5| page = 268}}</ref>\n\nAdams appeared on stage at two months old in the play ''The Lost Baby'' at the Salt Lake City Brigham Young Theatre.<ref name=\"Women of Character\">{{cite book|last1=Black|first1=Susan Easton| last2=Woodger| first2=Mary Jane| title=Women of Character|date=2011|publisher=Covenant Communications, Inc.|location=American Fork, UT|isbn=978-1-60861-212-3| pages=1\u20133}}</ref> She appeared again at the age of nine months in her mother's arms. Over her father's objections, Adams began acting as a small child, adopting her mother's maiden name as her stage name. They toured throughout the western U.S. with a theatrical troupe that played in rural areas, mining towns and some cities.<ref name=Utah/> At the age of five, Adams starred in a [[San Francisco]] theater as \"Little Schneider\" in ''Fritz, Our German Cousin'' and as \"Adrienne Renaud\" in ''A Celebrated Case''.<ref name=\"trivia-library.com\"/> At the age of nine, Adams lived with her Mormon grandmother and Mormon cousins in Salt Lake City, while her mother remained in San Francisco.<ref name=Mormons>{{cite book| last1=Hunter| first1=J. Michael|title=Mormons and Popular Culture: The Global Influence of an American Phenomenon|date=2013| publisher=Praeger| location=Santa Barbara| isbn=9780313391675| pages=135\u2013139|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171120162802/https://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2390&context=facpub| chapter=Maude Adams and the Mormons| archive-date=20 November 2017|url=https://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2390&context=facpub}}</ref> It is not clear whether she identified as a member of [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] as her mother did. She was never baptized Presbyterian, although she attended a Presbyterian school.<ref name=Mormons/> Later in life, Adams took long sabbaticals in Catholic convents, and in 1922 she donated her estates at [[Lake Ronkonkoma, New York]], to the [[Sisters of the Cenacle]], for use as a novitiate and retreat house.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.lakeronkonkomacivic.org/ronkonkoma/ronkonkoma.html |title=Lake Ronkonkoma History, Legends & Myths |url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100204081238/http://www.lakeronkonkomacivic.org/ronkonkoma/ronkonkoma.html |archivedate=2010-02-04 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.lakerhs.org/rhs/our%20town.htm#myths | title=Lake Ronkonkoma Historical Society | access-date=2017-03-31}}</ref> She never converted to Catholicism or discussed the topic in any interviews.<ref name=Mormons/>\n\nAdams debuted in New York at age ten in ''Esmeralda'' and then returned briefly to California. She then returned to Salt Lake City to live with her grandmother and studied at the Salt Lake Collegiate Institute.<ref name=Utah/> She later wrote of Salt Lake City, \"The people of the valley have gentle manners, as if their spirits moved with dignity.\"<ref name=RSobit/> Adams also later wrote a short essay, \"The One I Knew Least\", where she described her difficulty in discovering her own personality while playing so many theatrical roles as a child.<ref name=Utah/>\n\n==Early adult career==\n[[File:Adams Peter Pan.jpg|thumb|Adams as [[Peter Pan]]]]\nAdams returned to New York City at age 16 to appear in ''[[The Paymaster]]''.  She then became a member of [[E. H. Sothern]]'s theatre company in Boston, appearing in ''The Highest Bidder'', and then was on Broadway in ''[[Lord Chumley]]'' in 1888. [[Charles H. Hoyt]] then cast her in ''[[A Midnight Bell (play)|A Midnight Bell]]'' where audiences, if not the critics, took notice of her.  In 1889, sensing he had a potential new star on his hands, Hoyt offered her a five-year contract, but Adams declined in favor of a lesser offer from the powerful producer [[Charles Frohman]] who, from that point forward, took control of her career.  She soon left behind juvenile parts and began to play leading roles for Frohman,<ref name=Utah/> often alongside her mother.<ref>[http://www.ibdb.com/Person/View/29322 \"Annie Adams\"], [[Internet Broadway Database]], accessed January 20, 2016</ref> In 1890, Frohman asked [[David Belasco]] and [[Henry Churchill de Mille|Henry C. de Mille]] to specially write the part of Dora Prescott for Adams in their new play ''[[Men and Women (play)|Men and Women]]'', which Frohman was producing. The next year, she appeared as Nell in ''The Lost Paradise''.\n\nIn 1892, [[John Drew Jr.]] (one of the leading stars of the day) ended his 18-year association with [[Augustin Daly]] and joined Frohman's company. Frohman paired Adams and Drew in a series of plays beginning with ''[[The Masked Ball]]'' and ending with ''[[Rosemary (play)|Rosemary]]'' in 1896. She then spent five years as the leading lady in John Drew's company.<ref name=\"cp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.collectorspost.com/cgi-bin/ShopLoader.cgi?Actors/maude_adams.html|title=Maude Adams|publisher=Collectors Post|accessdate=2006-11-02}}</ref> There, \"her work was praised for its charm, delicacy, and simplicity.\"<ref name=Utah/> ''The Masked Ball'' opened on October 8, 1892.  Audiences came to see its star, Drew, but left remembering Adams. Most memorable was a scene in which her character feigned tipsiness for which she received a two-minute ovation on opening night. Drew was the star, but it was for Adams that the audience gave twelve curtain calls, and previously tepid critics gave generous reviews. ''Harpers Weekly'' wrote: \"It is difficult to see just who is going to prevent Miss Adams from becoming the leading exponent of light comedy in America.  ''The New York Times'' wrote that Adams, \"not John Drew, has made the success of ''The Masked Ball'' at Palmer's, and is the star of the comedy. Manager Charles Frohman, in attempting to exploit one star, has happened upon another of greater magnitude.\" The tipsy scene started Adams on her path to being a favorite among New York audiences and led to an eighteen-month run for the play.\n\nLess successful plays followed, including ''[[The Butterflies (play)|The Butterflies]]'', ''[[The Bauble Shop]]'', ''[[Christopher, Jr.]]'', ''[[The Imprudent Young Couple]]'' and ''[[The Squire of Dames]]''. But 1896 saw an upturn for Adams with ''Rosemary''. A comedy about the failed elopement of a young couple, sheltered for the night by an older man (Drew), the play received critical praise and box office success.<ref name=\"manybooks.net\">{{cite web|url=http://manybooks.net/pages/marcossoni2614626146-8/128.html|title=Charles Frohman: Manager and Man pr 128}}</ref>\n\n==Barrie and stardom==\n[[File:The-Little-Minister-1897.jpg|thumb|left|Adams and [[Robert Edeson]] in the Broadway production of ''The Little Minister'' (1897)]]\n[[File:Maude Adams in The Little Minister.jpg|thumb|upright|Poster for ''The Little Minister'' (1897)]]\n[[File:Mucha-Maud Adams as Joan of Arc-1909.jpg|thumb|upright|Adams as [[Joan of Arc]], painted by [[Alphonse Mucha]] (1909)]]\nFrohman had been pursuing [[J. M. Barrie]] (the future author of ''[[Peter and Wendy|Peter Pan]]'') to adapt the author's popular book ''The Little Minister'' into a play, but Barrie had resisted because he felt there was no actress who could play Lady Babbie. On a trip to New York in 1896, Barrie attended a performance of ''Rosemary'' and at once decided that Adams was the actress to play Lady Babbie.<ref name=\"manybooks.net\"/><ref name=Famous1>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/famousamericanac007101mbp/famousamericanac007101mbp_djvu.txt|title=Famous American Actors and Actresses, p. 92}}</ref> Frohman worried that the masculine aspects of the book might overshadow Adams's role. With Barrie's consent, several key scenes were changed to favor Lady Babbie.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://manybooks.net/pages/marcossoni2614626146-8/129.html|title=Charles Frohman: Manager and Man pr 129}}</ref> The play opened in 1897 at the [[Empire Theatre (41st Street)|Empire Theatre]] and was a tremendous success, running for 300 performances in New York (289 of which were standing room only) and setting a new all time box office record of $370,000; it made Adams a star.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://manybooks.net/pages/marcossoni2614626146-8/131.html|title=Charles Frohman: Manager and Man pr 131}}</ref><ref name=Famous1/> It also toured successfully, running for 65 performances in Boston.<ref name=Utah/>\n\nAnother play by Barrie, ''[[Peter and Wendy|Peter Pan; or, The Boy Who Wouldn't Grow Up]]'' (1904), became the role with which Adams was most closely identified.  She was the first actress to play [[Peter Pan]] on Broadway. Only days after her casting was announced, Adams had an emergency appendectomy, and it was uncertain whether her health would allow her to assume the role as planned. ''Peter Pan'' opened on October 16, 1905 at the [[National Theatre (Washington, D.C.)|National Theatre]] in Washington, D.C. to little success.<ref>{{cite book|last=Fields|first=Armond|title=Maude Adams|year=2004|publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc.|location=North Carolina|isbn=0-7864-1927-X|page=184}}</ref>  It soon moved to Broadway, however, where the play had a long run, and Adams appeared in the role on Broadway several times over the following decade.{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}} The collar of her 1905 Peter Pan costume, which she had co-designed, was an immediate fashion success and was henceforth known as the \"[[Peter Pan collar]]\".<ref name=Felsenthal>{{cite news|last=Felsenthal|first=Julia|title=Where the Peter Pan Collar Came From\u2014and Why It's Back|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2012/01/20/peter_pan_collar_where_it_came_from_and_why_it_s_back.html| accessdate=21 January 2012|newspaper=[[Slate Magazine]]|date=20 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nAdams starred in other works by Barrie, including ''[[Quality Street (play)|Quality Street]]'' (1901), ''[[What Every Woman Knows (play)|What Every Woman Knows]]'' (1908), ''[[The Legend of Leonora]]'' (1914), ''[[A Kiss for Cinderella]]'' (1916).  However, she also appeared in other works. In 1899, she portrayed Shakespeare's Juliet.  While audiences loved her in the role, selling out the sixteen performances in New York, the critics disliked it.{{citation needed|date=October 2013}}  ''[[Romeo and Juliet]]'' was followed by ''[[L'Aiglon]]'' in 1900, a French play about the life of [[Napoleon II of France]] in which Adams played the leading role, foreshadowing her portrayal of another male (Peter Pan) five years later.  The play had starred [[Sarah Bernhardt]] in Paris with enthusiastic reviews, but Adams's ''L'Aiglon'' received mixed reviews in New York. In 1909, she played Joan of Arc in [[Friedrich Schiller]]'s ''[[The Maid of Orleans (play)|The Maid of Orleans]]''.  This was produced on a huge scale at the [[Harvard University]] Stadium by Frohman.<ref>\"Maude Adams in a Rehearsal of \"Joan of Arc\" at the Stadium. ''[[The New York Times]]'', May 30, 1909</ref> The June 24, 1909 edition of the ''Paducah Evening Sun'' (Kentucky) contains the following excerpt:\n\n<blockquote>Joan at Harvard, Schiller's Play reproduced on Gigantic scale. \u2026 The experiment of producing Schiller's \"Maid of Orleans\" beneath starry skies \u2026 was carried out \u2026 by ... Adams and a company numbering about two thousand persons \u2026 at the Harvard Stadium. \u2026  A special electric light plant was installed \u2026 a great cathedral was erected, background constructed and a realistic forest created. \u2026  Miss Adams was accorded an ovation at the end of the performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85052114/1909-06-24/ed-1/seq-2/ |title='&#39;The Paducah Evening Sun'&#39; excerpt (06/24/1909) |publisher=Chroniclingamerica.loc.gov |date=1909-06-24 |accessdate=2014-02-07}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nShe appeared in another French play with 1911's ''[[Chantecler (play)|Chantecler]]'', the story of a rooster who believes his crowing makes the sun rise.<ref name=\"Broadway by Ken Bloom pg 8\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rqi3d1925IcC&pg=PA51&lpg=PA51&dq=Ethel+Barrymore+understudy+Maude+Adams&source=web&ots=cb-hQJxt_Q&sig=7Zxwx5h_cpnU6i6o4y2-f2xTYYI&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=1&ct=result#PPA8,M1|title=Broadway by Ken Bloom pg 8}}</ref> She fared only slightly better than in ''L'Aiglon'' with the critics, but audiences again embraced her, on one occasion giving her twenty two curtain calls.<ref name=\"Broadway by Ken Bloom pg 8\"/> Adams later cited it as her favorite role, with Peter Pan a close second.\n\n==Retirement and death==\nAdams retired in 1918 after a severe bout of [[influenza]].<ref name=\"harbin\">{{Cite book |title=The Gay & Lesbian Theatrical Legacy: A Biographical Dictionary of Major Figures in American Stage History in the Pre-Stonewall Era |year=2005 |publisher=University of Michigan Press |pages=16\u201318 |editor-last=Harbin |editor-first=Billy J. |editor2-last=Marra |editor2-first=Kim |editor3-last=Schanke |editor3-first=Robert A. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f0fbSlGN8uUC&pg=PA16}}</ref> During the 1920s, she worked with [[General Electric]] to develop improved and more powerful stage lighting and with the Eastman Company in developing color photography.  It has been suggested that her motivation for her association with these technology companies was because she wished to appear in a color film version of ''Peter Pan'', and this would have required better lighting and techniques for color photography.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trivia-library.com/a/famous-stage-actress-biography-of-maude-adams.htm |title=Trivia on Famous Stage Actress Biography of Maude Adams |publisher=Trivia Library |date= |accessdate=2014-02-07}}</ref>  After 13 years away from the stage, she returned to acting, appearing occasionally in regional productions of [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]] plays, including as Portia in ''[[The Merchant of Venice]]'' in Ohio, in 1931, and as Maria in ''[[Twelfth Night]]'' in 1934 in Maine.<ref name=Utah/>\n\nOften described as shy, Adams was referred to by [[Ethel Barrymore]] as the \"original [[Greta Garbo#Public persona|'I want to be alone' woman]]\".<ref>{{Cite book |title=The Great White Way: a re-creation of Broadway's golden era of theatrical entertainment |page=107 |year=1962 |publisher=Dutton |first=Allen |last=Churchill}}</ref> Her retiring lifestyle, including the absence of any relationships with men, contributed to the virtuous and innocent public image promoted by Frohman and was reflected in her most successful roles. Biographers have concluded that Adams was a lesbian.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Fd7BAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA114 |title=Making American Culture |first=Patricia |last=Bradley |year=2009 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Madsen| first1=Axel| title=The Sewing Circle: Sappho's Leading Ladies|date=February 2002|publisher=Kensington Publishing Corporation|location=New York City|isbn=978-0758201010|page=3| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QwxFfhiFcAAC&lpg=PA243&pg=PA3}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Schanke|first1=Robert A.|title=That Furious Lesbian: The Story of Mercedes de Acosta|date=10 May 2004| publisher=Southern Illinois University Press| isbn=0809325799|page=14|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LesZDgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA14&pg=PA14}}</ref> She had two long-term relationships that only ended upon her partners' deaths: Lillie Florence, from the early 1890s until 1901, and Louise Boynton (1858\u20131951) from 1905 until 1951.<ref name=\"harbin\"/><ref name=\"Legacy\">{{cite book|last1=Harbin|first1=Billy J.|last2=Marra|first2=Kimberley Bell|last3=Schanke|first3=Robert A.|title=The Gay and Lesbian Theatrical Legacy: A Biographical Dictionary of Major Figures in American Stage History in the Pre-Stonewall Era|date=28 March 2007|publisher=University of Michigan Press|isbn=978-0472068586|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f0fbSlGN8uUC&lpg=PA18&ots=lKK89j4hPP&pg=PA15}}</ref>{{rp|16}} She is supposed to have had a romantic relationship with actress [[Spring Byington]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bendix|first1=Trish|title=The Gay Women of Old Hollywood|url=http://www.newnownext.com/the-gay-women-of-old-hollywood/09/2010| website=newnownext.com| publisher=Viacom International Inc.|date=1 September 2010}}</ref> Adams was known at times to supplement the salaries of fellow performers out of her own pay.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}} Once while touring, a theater owner significantly raised the price of tickets, knowing Adams's name meant a sold-out house. Adams made the owner refund the difference before she appeared on the stage that night.<ref>Robbins (1956), p. 219</ref> Adams was the head of the drama department at [[Stephens College]] in Missouri from 1937 to 1949, becoming known as an inspiring teacher in the arts of acting.<ref name=\"cp\"/><ref>Fields, p. 299</ref>\n\nAfter her retirement, Adams was on occasion pursued for roles in film. The closest she came to accepting was in 1938, when producer David O. Selznick persuaded her to do a screen test (with [[Janet Gaynor]], who would later play the female lead) for the role of Miss Fortune in the film ''[[The Young in Heart]]''. After negotiations failed, the role was played by [[Minnie Dupree]]. The twelve-minute screen test was preserved by the George Eastman House in 2004.<ref name=\"bampfa preserved\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bampfa.berkeley.edu/event/young-heart-0 |title=The Young in Heart |publisher=[[Berkeley Art Museum and Pacific Film Archive]] |accessdate=April 21, 2017 |archivedate=April 22, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170422135937/http://www.bampfa.berkeley.edu/event/young-heart-0 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nShe died, aged 80, at her summer home, Caddam Hill, in [[Tannersville, New York]], and is interred in the cemetery of the [[Sisters of the Cenacle]], [[Lake Ronkonkoma, New York]]<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.lioddities.com/Maude%20Adams/MaudeAdams.htm| title=Long Island Oddities| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080915021200/http://www.lioddities.com/Maude%20Adams/MaudeAdams.htm| archivedate=2008-09-15}}</ref> and Louise Boynton is buried alongside her.<ref>Wilson, Scott. ''Resting Places: The Burial Sites of More Than 14,000 Famous Persons'', 3d ed.: 2. McFarland & Company (2016) {{ISBN|0786479922}} In 1898, Adams purchased a farm in Lake Ronkonkoma called Sandy Garth, which in 1922 she donated to the Sisters of St. Regis, and had the Cenacle Retreat House built for them. See {{Cite book |title=Images of America: Lake Ronkonkoma |page=88 |year=2011 |publisher=Arcadia Publishing |first=Keith |last=Oswald |first2=Dale |last2=Spencer}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe character of Elise McKenna in [[Richard Matheson]]'s 1975 novel ''[[Bid Time Return]]'' and its 1980 film adaptation, ''[[Somewhere in Time (film)|Somewhere in Time]]'', in which the character was played by [[Jane Seymour (actress)|Jane Seymour]], was based on Maude Adams.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/600137031/Legendary-sci-fi-author-tackles-social-commentary.html?pg=all|title=Legendary sci-fi author tackles social commentary|work=Deseret News|date=2005-05-29|accessdate=2014-04-07}}</ref> In the novel, Elise is appearing in ''The Little Minister'', which role was also said to have been written especially for her. {{citation needed|date=December 2009}}\n[[File:Maude Adams as Phoebe in Quality Street.jpg|thumb|upright|Adams as Phoebe in ''[[Quality Street (play)|Quality Street]]'' (1901)]]\n\n==Broadway appearances==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[The Paymaster]]'' \u2013 1888\n* ''[[Lord Chumley]]'' \u2013 1888\n* ''[[A Midnight Bell (play)|A Midnight Bell]]'' \u2013 1889\n* ''[[Men and Women (play)|Men and Women]]'' \u2013 1890\n* ''[[The Masked Ball]]'' \u2013 1892\n* ''[[The Butterflies (play)|The Butterflies]]'' \u2013 1894\n* ''[[The Bauble Shop]]'' \u2013 1894\n* ''[[The Imprudent Young Couple]]'' \u2013 1895\n* ''[[Christopher, Jr.]]'' \u2013 1895\n* ''[[The Squire of Dames]]'' \u2013 1896\n* ''[[Rosemary (play)|Rosemary]]'' \u2013 1896\n* ''The Little Minister'' \u2013 1897 and 1904\n* ''[[Romeo and Juliet]]'' \u2013 1899\n* ''[[L'Aiglon (play)|L'Aiglon]]'' \u2013 1900\n* ''[[Quality Street (play)|Quality Street]]'' \u2013 1901\n* ''[[The Pretty Sister of Jose]]'' \u2013 1903\n* ''[['Op o' Me Thumb]]'' \u2013 1905\n* ''[[Peter Pan]]'' \u2013 1905, 1906, 1912 and 1915\n* ''[[Quality Street (play)|Quality Street]]'' \u2013 1908\n* ''The Jesters'' \u2013 1908\n* ''[[The-Merry-Go-Round]]'' \u2013 1908\n* ''[[What Every Woman Knows (play)|What Every Woman Knows]]'' \u2013 1908\n* ''[[Chantecler (play)|Chantecler]]'' \u2013 1911\n* ''[[The Legend of Leonora]]'' \u2013 1914\n* ''The Little Minister'' \u2013 1916\n* ''[[A Kiss for Cinderella]]'' \u2013 1916\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uw5HrxKyIR4C&dq=Christopher,+Jr.++Maude+Adams&source=gbs_navlinks_s| title=Maude Adams: Idol of American Theater, 1872-1953| author=[[Armond Fields]]| publisher=McFarland| year=2004|isbn=978-0-7864-1927-2}}\n* {{Cite book| last1 = Marcosson| first1 = Isaac Frederick| authorlink=Isaac Frederick Marcosson| last2 = Frohman| first2 = Daniel| title = Charles Frohman: Manager and Man| publisher = John Lane, The Bodley Head| url=https://archive.org/details/charlesfrohmanma00marc| date = 1916}}\n*Robbins, Phyllis. ''Maude Adams: An Intimate Portrait'' (1956)\n*Robbins, Phyllis. ''The Young Maude Adams'' (1959)\n* {{citation|last=Stern|first=Keith|chapter=Maude Adams|title=Queers in History|publisher=BenBella Books, Inc.; Dallas, Texas|year=2009|isbn=978-1-933771-87-8}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography|LGBT}}\n{{commons category|Maude Adams}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{IMDb name|5155958}}\n* {{NYPL Digital Gallery keyword|Maude Adams}} held by the Billy Rose Theatre Division, [[New York Public Library for the Performing Arts]]\n* [http://archives.nypl.org/the/21337 Maude Adams collection, 1879-1956], held by the Billy Rose Theatre Division, [[New York Public Library for the Performing Arts]]\n* {{Find a Grave|8}}\n*[https://archive.today/20130131040538/http://www.periodpaper.com/index.php/1910-maude-adams-actress-peter-pan-will-bradley-print Maude Adams; PeriodPaper.com c. 1910]\n* [http://www.booklibris.com/MaudeAdamsBiographiesList.htm Maude Adams profile and list of biographies]\n* [http://gutenberg.org/files/57611/57611-h/57611-h.htm Heroines of The Modern Stage] p.324 by Forrest Izard c.1915\n* {{Wikisource-inline|list=\n** {{Cite NIE|wstitle=Adams, Maude Kiskadden|year=1905|short=x |noicon=x}}\n** {{Cite Americana|wstitle=Adams, Maud Kiskadden|year=1920 |short=x |noicon=x}}\n** {{Cite Collier's|wstitle=Adams, Maude Kiskadden|year=1921|short=x |noicon=x}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adams, Maude}}\n[[Category:1872 births]]\n[[Category:1953 deaths]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:19th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Lesbian actresses]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Utah]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Salt Lake City]]\n[[Category:Stephens College faculty]]\n", "name_user": "T.M. Tucker4history", "label": "safe", "comment": "I incerted facts that I found and cited those of the critics on her as Juliet, according to the New York Journal and Advertiser and her as Peter Pan on Broadway being a success according to the New York Herald, 1906. I also added the external link, Better Days 2020.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maude_Adams"}
{"title_page": "List of cyberpunk works", "text_new": "This is a list of works classified as [[cyberpunk]], a [[subgenre]] of [[science fiction]]. Cyberpunk is characterized by a focus on \"[[high tech]] and low life\" in a near-future setting.<ref>Anonymous. (2009). [http://www.cyberpunked.org/cyberpunk/ What is cyberpunk?] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190110175329/https://www.cyberpunked.org/cyberpunk/ |date=2019-01-10 }} ''Cyberpunked: Journal of Science, Technology, &amp; Society''.</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Ketterer |first=David |authorlink= |title=Canadian Science Fiction and Fantasy |url=https://archive.org/details/canadiansciencef00davi |url-access=registration |quote=Cyberpunk high-tech low-life. |publisher=[[Indiana University Press]] |year=1992 |page=[https://archive.org/details/canadiansciencef00davi/page/141 141] |isbn=0-253-33122-6}}</ref>\n\n==Print media==\n===Novels and novellas===\n* ''[[Do Androids Dream of Electric Sheep?]]'' (1968) [[Philip K. Dick]]\n* ''[[True Names]]'' (1981) by [[Vernor Vinge]]<ref>{{cite web|work=Publishers Weekly|title=TRUE NAMES: And the Opening of the Cyberspace Frontier [book review]|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-312-86207-7|quote=the story that began SF's cyberpunk revolution}}</ref>\n* ''[[Ware Tetralogy]]'' (1982\u20132000) by [[Rudy Rucker]]<ref name=markoff>{{cite news | first=John | last=Markoff | title=Ideas & Trends; Art Invents A Jarring New World From Technology | url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE7D8133FF936A15752C1A966958260&sec=&spon=&&scp=10&sq=cyberpunk&st=cse | work=The New York Times | date=1990-11-25 | accessdate=2009-02-03}}</ref><ref name=\"markoff\" />\n* ''[[Neuromancer]]'' (1984) by [[William Gibson]]\n* ''[[Dr. Adder]]'' (1984) by [[K. W. Jeter]]<ref name=handbook>{{cite book|title=The Science Fiction Handbook|last1=Booker|first1=M. Keith|last2=Thomas|first2=Anne-Marie|date=2009|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uW9xST9UsOIC|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9781444310351}}</ref>\n* The ''[[Sprawl trilogy]]'' (1984\u20131988) by [[William Gibson]] \u2013 popularized the concept of [[cyberspace]], exemplifies the genre.<ref name=handbook/><ref name=\"handbook\" /><ref name=handbook/><ref>{{cite web|title=Study Guide for William Gibson: Neuromancer (1984) |url=http://www.wsu.edu/~brians/science_fiction/neuromancer.html |accessdate=2007-01-15 |date=1998-12-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061224081742/http://www.wsu.edu/~brians/science_fiction/neuromancer.html |archivedate=2006-12-24 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\"Count Zero\" Book review|url=http://www.novelreflections.com/reviews/william-gibson/count-zero|accessdate=2009-02-04|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090301153545/http://www.novelreflections.com/reviews/william-gibson/count-zero|archivedate=2009-03-01}}</ref>\n* ''[[Schismatrix]]'' (1985) by [[Bruce Sterling]]<ref name=mason>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4QOyAAAAQBAJ|last=Mason|first=Fran|title=Historical Dictionary of Postmodernist Literature and Theater|date=2007|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=9780810864542}}</ref><ref name=beyond>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lh7JBQAAQBAJ|title=Beyond Cyberpunk: New Critical Perspectives|last1=Murphy|first1=Graham J.|last2=Vint|first2=Sherryl|date=2010|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781136973178}}</ref>\n* ''[[Eclipse Trilogy]]'' (also known as ''A Song Called Youth Trilogy'') (1985\u201390) by [[John Shirley]] \u2013 includes ''Eclipse'' (1985), ''Eclipse Penumbra'' (1988), and ''Eclipse Corona'' (1990)<ref name=markoff/><ref name=mason/>\n* ''[[Hardwired (novel)|Hardwired]]'' (1986) by [[Walter Jon Williams]]<ref name=beyond/>\n* ''[[Mindplayers]]'' (1987) by [[Pat Cadigan]]<ref name=mason/>\n* ''[[The Glass Hammer]]'' (1987) by [[K. W. Jeter]]\n* ''[[Voice of the Whirlwind]]'' (1987) by [[Walter Jon Williams]]<ref>{{cite web| title=Cyberpunk Fiction: The Visionary Kaleidoscope| url=http://mars.superlink.net/~neptune/Cyberpnk.html| accessdate=2009-02-04| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100707013937/http://mars.superlink.net/~neptune/Cyberpnk.html| archivedate=2010-07-07}}</ref>\n* ''[[When Gravity Fails]]'' (1987) by [[George Alec Effinger]] \u2013 part of the Effinger's Mar\u00eed Audran series<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sfsignal.com/archives/2005/11/review-when-gravity-fails-by-george-alec-effinger/ |title=REVIEW: When Gravity Fails by George Alec Effinger |publisher=SF Signal |accessdate=2009-05-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090628070551/http://www.sfsignal.com/archives/2005/11/review-when-gravity-fails-by-george-alec-effinger/ |archivedate=2009-06-28 }}</ref>\n* ''[[Islands in the Net]]'' (1988) by [[Bruce Sterling]]<ref name=\"mason\" />\n* ''[[A Fire in the Sun]]'' (1989) by [[George Alec Effinger]] \u2013 part of the Effinger's Mar\u00eed Audran series\n* ''[[Solip:System]]'' (1989) by [[Walter Jon Williams]]<ref>{{cite web | title=A Cascade Of Invention Walter Jon Williams | url=http://www.zone-sf.com/walterjonw.html | accessdate=2009-02-04 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206102942/http://www.zone-sf.com/walterjonw.html | archive-date=2008-12-06 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* ''[[My Cousin, My Gastroenterologist]]'' (1990) by [[Mark Leyner]]{{Citation needed|date=October 2013}}\n* ''[[The Exile Kiss]]'' (1991) by [[George Alec Effinger]] \u2013 part of the Effinger's Mar\u00eed Audran series\n* ''[[Synners]]'' (1991) by [[Pat Cadigan]]<ref name=\"mason\" />\n* ''[[Snow Crash]]'' (1992) by [[Neal Stephenson]]\n* The ''[[Bridge trilogy]]'' (1993\u20131999) by [[William Gibson]]<ref>{{cite web|title=\"Virtual Light\" review|url=http://project.cyberpunk.ru/idb/virtuallight.html|accessdate= 2009-02-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\"Idoru\" review|url=http://project.cyberpunk.ru/idb/idoru.html|accessdate= 2009-02-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\"All 